# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: association-for-manufacturing-technology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/ansi] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/association-for-manufacturing-technology] The **Association for Manufacturing Technology** (**AMT**) is a trade association based in McLean, Virginia, in the United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/association-for-manufacturing-technology] It was founded as the National Machine Tool Builders' Association (NMTBA) in 1902.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/association-for-manufacturing-technology] It represents and promotes the interests of American providers of manufacturing machinery and equipment.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/association-for-manufacturing-technology] As machine tools advanced, NMTBA launched the first National Machine Tool Builders’ Exposition in 1927, which would later be rebranded IMTS- International Manufacturing Technology Show.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/association-for-manufacturing-technology] The AMT’s most visible activity is its management of the International Manufacturing Technology Show (IMTS), which is held on even-numbered years at McCormick Place in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/association-for-manufacturing-technology] AMT also supports their membership with technology centers and representative offices in China, India, Poland, Mexico and Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/association-for-manufacturing-technology] AMT puts on a number of events throughout the year.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/association-for-manufacturing-technology] While IMTS takes place in every even year, AMT also hosts the MFG Meeting and MTForecast Conference every year.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Bounded by the Atlantic Ocean on the east, Brazil has a coastline of 7,491 kilometers (4,655 mi), among the longest in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Covering roughly half of South America's land area, it borders all other countries and territories on the continent except Ecuador and Chile.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil encompasses a wide range of tropical and subtropical landscapes, as well as wetlands, savannas, plateaus, and low mountains.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] It contains most of the Amazon basin, including the world's largest river system and most extensive virgin tropical forest.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil has diverse wildlife, a variety of ecological systems, and extensive natural resources spanning numerous protected habitats.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] It ranks first among 17 megadiverse countries, with its natural heritage being the subject of significant global interest, as environmental degradation (through processes such as deforestation) directly affect global issues such as climate change and biodiversity loss.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil was inhabited by various indigenous peoples prior to the landing of Portuguese explorer Pedro Álvares Cabral in 1500.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The territory was subsequently claimed and settled by Portugal, which founded the country's first city, São Vicente, in 1532 and imported enslaved Africans to work on plantations.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil remained a colony until 1815, when it was elevated to a united kingdom with Portugal after the transfer of the Portuguese court to Rio de Janeiro.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Prince Pedro of Braganza declared Brazilian independence in 1822 and, after waging a war against Portugal, established the Empire of Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The country's first constitution in 1824 established a bicameral legislature and enshrined principles such as freedom of religion and the press; slavery was gradually abolished until its final abolition in 1888.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil became a presidential republic following a military coup d'état in 1889.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] An armed revolution in 1930 ended the First Republic and brought Getúlio Vargas to power.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Vargas' self-coup in 1937 ushered the authoritarian Estado Novo, in which he oversaw Brazil's involvement in World War II.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Democracy was restored after Vargas' ousting in 1945.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] An authoritarian military dictatorship emerged in 1964 with support from the United States and ruled until 1985, after which civilian governance resumed.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil's current constitution, enacted in 1988, defines it as a democratic federal republic.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil is a regional and middle power, and has been described as a rising global power.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] It is an emerging, upper-middle income economy and newly industrialized country, with one of the 10 largest economies in the world in both nominal and PPP terms, the largest economy in Latin America and the Southern Hemisphere, and the largest share of wealth in South America.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] With a complex and highly diversified economy, Brazil is one of the world's major or primary exporters of various agricultural goods, mineral resources, and manufactured products.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The country ranks thirteenth in the world by number of UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil is a founding member of the United Nations, the G20, BRICS, G4, Mercosur, Organization of American States, Organization of Ibero-American States, and the Community of Portuguese Language Countries; it is also an observer state of the Arab League and a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The word *Brazil* probably comes from the Portuguese word for brazilwood, a tree that once grew plentifully along the Brazilian coast.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In Portuguese, brazilwood is called *pau-brasil*, with the word *brasil* commonly given the etymology 'red like an ember', formed from *brasa* ('ember') and the suffix *-il* (from *-iculum* or *-ilium*).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] It has alternatively been suggested that this is a folk etymology for a word for the plant related to an Arabic or Asian word for a red plant.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] As brazilwood produces a deep red dye, it was highly valued by the European textile industry and was the earliest commercially exploited product from Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Throughout the 16th century, massive amounts of brazilwood were harvested by indigenous peoples (mostly Tupi) along the Brazilian coast, who sold the timber to European traders in return for assorted European consumer goods.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The official Portuguese name of the land, in original Portuguese records, was the 'Land of the Holy Cross' (*Terra da Santa Cruz*), but European sailors and merchants commonly called it the 'Land of Brazil' (*Terra do Brasil*) because of the brazilwood trade.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Popular usage eclipsed and eventually supplanted the official Portuguese name.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Some early sailors called it the 'Land of Parrots'.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In the Guarani language, Brazil is called *Pindorama*, meaning 'land of the palm trees'.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Some of the earliest human remains found in the Americas, Luzia Woman, were found in the area of Pedro Leopoldo, Minas Gerais, and provide evidence of human habitation going back at least 11,000 years.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The earliest pottery ever found in the Western Hemisphere was excavated in the Amazon basin of Brazil and radiocarbon dated to over 8,000 years ago (6000 BC).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The pottery was found near Santarém and provides evidence that the region supported a complex prehistoric culture.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The Marajoara culture flourished on Marajó in the Amazon delta from AD 400 to 1400, developing sophisticated pottery, social stratification, large populations, mound building, and complex social formations such as chiefdoms.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Around the time of the Portuguese arrival, the territory of present day Brazil had an estimated Indigenous population of 7 million people, mostly semi-nomadic, who subsisted on hunting, fishing, gathering, and migrant agriculture.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The population comprised several large Indigenous ethnic groups (e.g., the Tupis, Guaranis, and Gês.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The Tupi people were subdivided into the Tupiniquins and Tupinambás.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Before the arrival of the Europeans, the boundaries between these groups and their subgroups were marked by wars that arose from differences in culture, language and moral beliefs.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] These wars also involved large-scale military actions on land and water, with cannibalistic rituals on prisoners of war.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] While heredity had some weight, leadership was a status more won over time than assigned in succession ceremonies and conventions.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Slavery among the Indigenous groups had a different meaning than it had for Europeans, since it originated from a diverse socioeconomic organization, in which asymmetries were translated into kinship relations.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Following the 1494 Treaty of Tordesillas, the land now called Brazil was claimed for the Portuguese Empire on 22 April 1500, with the arrival of the Portuguese fleet commanded by Pedro Álvares Cabral.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Along the coast, the Portuguese encountered various Indigenous communities, most of whom spoke languages of the Tupi–Guarani family.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Though the first settlement, São Vicente, was founded in 1532, colonization effectively began in 1534, when King John III of Portugal divided the territory into the fifteen private and autonomous captaincies.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] However, the decentralized and unorganized captaincy system proved unsuccessful, and in 1549 the Portuguese king restructured them into the Governorate General of Brazil in the city of Salvador, which became the capital of a single and centralized Portuguese colony in South America.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In the first two centuries of colonization, Indigenous and European groups lived in constant war, establishing opportunistic alliances in order to gain advantages against each other.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil received more than 2.8 million slaves from Africa between the years 1500 and 1800.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] This increased level of immigration in turn caused some conflicts between newcomers and old settlers.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Portuguese expeditions known as *bandeiras* gradually expanded Brazil's original colonial frontiers in South America to its approximately current borders.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In this era, other European powers tried to colonize parts of Brazil, in incursions that the Portuguese had to fight, notably the French in Rio during the 1560s, in Maranhão during the 1610s, and the Dutch in Bahia and Pernambuco, during the Dutch–Portuguese War, after the end of Iberian Union.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In late 1807, Spanish and Napoleonic forces threatened the security of continental Portugal, causing Prince Regent John, in the name of Queen Maria I, to move the royal court from Lisbon to Rio de Janeiro.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] There they established some of Brazil's first financial institutions, such as its local stock exchanges and its National Bank, additionally ending the Portuguese monopoly on Brazilian trade and opening Brazil's ports to other nations.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In 1809, in retaliation for being forced into exile, the Prince Regent ordered the conquest of French Guiana.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] With the end of the Peninsular War in 1814, the courts of Europe demanded that Queen Maria I and Prince Regent John return to Portugal, deeming it unfit for the head of an ancient European monarchy to reside in a colony.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In 1815, to justify continuing to live in Brazil, where the royal court had thrived for six years, the Crown established the United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves, thus creating a pluricontinental transatlantic monarchic state.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] However, the leadership in Portugal, resentful of the new status of its larger colony, continued to demand the return of the court to Lisbon (see Liberal Revolution of 1820).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In 1821, acceding to the demands of revolutionaries who had taken the city of Porto, John VI departed for Lisbon.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] There he swore an oath to the new constitution, leaving his son, Prince Pedro de Alcântara, as Regent of the Kingdom of Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Tensions between Portuguese and Brazilians increased and the Portuguese Cortes, guided by the new political regime imposed by the Liberal Revolution, tried to re-establish Brazil as a colony.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The Brazilians refused to yield, and Prince Pedro decided to side with them, declaring the country's independence from Portugal on 7 September 1822.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] A month later, Prince Pedro was proclaimed the first Emperor of Brazil, with the royal title of Dom Pedro I, resulting in the founding of the Empire of Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The Brazilian War of Independence, which had already begun along this process, spread through the northern, northeastern regions and in the Cisplatina province.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The last Portuguese soldiers surrendered on 8 March 1824; Portugal officially recognized Brazilian independence on 29 August 1825.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] As the new Emperor could not exert his constitutional powers until he came of age, a regency was set up by the General Assembly.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] These emerged from the provinces' dissatisfaction with the central power, coupled with old and latent social tensions peculiar to a vast, slaveholding and newly independent nation state.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] This period of internal political and social upheaval, which included the Praieira revolt in Pernambuco, was overcome only at the end of the 1840s, years after the end of the regency, which occurred with the premature coronation of Pedro II in 1841.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] During the last phase of the monarchy, internal political debate centered on the issue of slavery.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The foreign-affairs policies of the monarchy dealt with issues pertaining Brazil's neighboring countries in the Southern Cone.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Long after the Cisplatine War that resulted in the independence of Uruguay, Brazil won three international wars during the 58-year reign of Pedro II: the Platine War, the Uruguayan War and the devastating Paraguayan War, the largest war effort in Brazilian history.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Although there was no desire among the majority of Brazilians to change the country's form of government, on 15 November 1889, in disagreement with the majority of the Imperial Army officers, as well as with rural and financial elites, the monarchy was overthrown by a military coup.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] A few days later, the national flag was replaced with a new design that included the national motto "*Ordem e Progresso*", influenced by positivism.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] 15 November is now Republic Day, a national holiday.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The early republican government was a military dictatorship, with the army dominating affairs both in Rio de Janeiro and in the states.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Freedom of the press disappeared and elections were controlled by those in power.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Not until 1894, following an economic crisis and a military one, did civilians take power, remaining there until October 1930.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Vargas and the military were supposed to assume power temporarily, but instead closed down Congress, extinguished the Constitution, ruled with emergency powers and replaced the states' governors with his own supporters.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In the 1930s, three attempts to remove Vargas and his supporters from power failed.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The first was the Constitutionalist Revolution in 1932, led by São Paulo's oligarchy.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The second was a communist uprising in November 1935, and the third a *putsch* attempt by local fascists in May 1938.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The 1935 uprising created a security crisis in which Congress transferred more power to the executive branch.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The 1937 *coup d'état* resulted in the cancellation of the 1938 election and formalized Vargas as dictator, beginning the Estado Novo era.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] During this period, government brutality and censorship of the press increased.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] During World War II, Brazil remained neutral until August 1942, when the country suffered retaliation by Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy in a strategic dispute over the South Atlantic, and, therefore, entered the war on the allied side.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In addition to its participation in the battle of the Atlantic, Brazil also sent an expeditionary force to fight in the Italian campaign.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] With the Allied victory in 1945 and the end of the fascist regimes in Europe, Vargas' position became untenable, and he was swiftly overthrown in another military coup, with democracy reinstated by the same army that had ended it 15 years earlier.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Vargas committed suicide in August 1954 amid a political crisis, after having returned to power by election in 1950.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Several brief interim governments followed Vargas' suicide.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Juscelino Kubitschek became president in 1956 and assumed a conciliatory stance towards the political opposition that allowed him to govern without major crises.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The economy and industrial sector grew remarkably, but his greatest achievement was the construction of the new capital city of Brasília, inaugurated in 1960.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Kubitschek's successor, Jânio Quadros, resigned in 1961 less than a year after taking office.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] His vice-president, João Goulart, assumed the presidency, but aroused strong political opposition and was deposed in April 1964 by a coup that resulted in a military dictatorship.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The new regime was intended to be transitory, but gradually closed in on itself and became a full dictatorship with the promulgation of the Fifth Institutional Act in 1968.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Oppression was not limited to those who resorted to guerrilla tactics to fight the regime, but also reached institutional opponents, artists, journalists and other members of civil society, inside and outside the country through "Operation Condor".
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Like other authoritarian regimes, due to an economic boom, known as the "economic miracle", the Brazilian military dictatorship reached a peak in popularity in the early 1970s.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Slowly, however, the wear and tear of years of dictatorial power had not slowed the repression, even after the defeat of the leftist guerrillas.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The inability to deal with the economic crises of the period and popular pressure made a redemocratization policy inevitable, which from the regime side was led by Generals Ernesto Geisel and Golbery do Couto e Silva.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] With the enactment of the Amnesty Law in 1979, Brazil began a slow return to democracy, which was completed during the 1980s.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Civilians returned to power in 1985 when José Sarney assumed the presidency.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] He became unpopular during his tenure through failure to control the economic crisis and hyperinflation he inherited from the military regime.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Sarney's unsuccessful government led to the election in 1989 of the almost-unknown Fernando Collor, who was subsequently impeached by the National Congress in 1992.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Collor was succeeded by his vice-president, Itamar Franco, who appointed Fernando Henrique Cardoso as Minister of Finance.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In 1994, Cardoso devised a highly successful Plano Real that, after decades of failed economic plans made by previous governments attempting to curb hyperinflation, finally stabilized the Brazilian economy.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Cardoso won the 1994 election, and again in 1998.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The peaceful transition of power from Cardoso to his main opposition leader, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva (elected in 2002 and re-elected in 2006), was seen as proof that Brazil had achieved a long-sought political stability.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Rousseff was impeached by the Brazilian Congress in 2016, halfway into her second term, and replaced by her vice-president Michel Temer, who assumed full presidential powers after Rousseff's impeachment was accepted on 31 August.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Large street protests for and against her took place during the impeachment process.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The charges against her were fueled by political and economic crises along with evidence of involvement with politicians from all the primary political parties.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In 2017, the Supreme Court requested the investigation of 71 Brazilian lawmakers and nine ministers of President Michel Temer's cabinet who were allegedly linked to the Petrobras corruption scandal.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] President Temer himself was also accused of corruption.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In the fiercely contested 2018 elections, the controversial conservative candidate Jair Bolsonaro of the Social Liberal Party (PSL) was elected president, winning in the second round against Fernando Haddad, of the Workers Party (PT), with the support of 55.13% of the valid votes.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In the early 2020s, Brazil became one of the hardest hit countries during the COVID-19 pandemic, receiving the second-highest death toll worldwide after the United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In May 2021, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva stated that he would run for a third term in the 2022 Brazilian general election against Bolsonaro.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In October 2022, Lula was in first place in the first round, with 48.43% of the support from the electorate, and received 50.90% of the votes in the second round.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] On 8 January 2023, a week after Lula's inauguration, a mob of Bolsonaro's supporters attacked Brazil's federal government buildings in the capital, Brasília, after several weeks of unrest.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil occupies nearly half of the land area of South America (47.7%), including a large area along its eastern coast and much of the continent's interior.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] It borders Uruguay to the south; Argentina and Paraguay to the southwest; Bolivia and Peru to the west; Colombia to the northwest; and Venezuela, Guyana, Suriname, and France (French overseas region of French Guiana) to the north.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] It shares a border with every South American country except Ecuador and Chile.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The Brazilian territory also encompasses a number of oceanic archipelagos, such as Fernando de Noronha, Rocas Atoll, Saint Peter and Saint Paul Archipelago, and the islands of Trindade and Martim Vaz.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Its size, relief, climate, and natural resources make Brazil geographically diverse.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Including its Atlantic islands, Brazil lies between latitudes 6°N and 34°S, and longitudes 28° and 74°W.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil is the fifth largest country in the world, and third largest in the Americas, with a total area of 8,515,767.049 km2 (3,287,956 sq mi), including 55,455 km2 (21,411 sq mi) of water.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil is the only country in the world that has the equator and the Tropic of Capricorn running through it.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] It spans four time zones; from UTC−5 comprising the state of Acre and the westernmost portion of Amazonas, to UTC−4 in the western states, to UTC−3 in the eastern states (the national time) and UTC−2 in the Atlantic islands.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The climate of Brazil comprises a wide range of weather conditions across a large area and varied topography, but most of the country is tropical.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] According to the Köppen system, Brazil hosts six major climatic subtypes: desert, equatorial, tropical, semiarid, oceanic and subtropical.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The different climatic conditions produce environments ranging from equatorial rainforests in the north and semiarid deserts in the northeast, to temperate coniferous forests in the south and tropical savannas in central Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In Brazil, forest cover is around 59% of the total land area, equivalent to 496,619,600 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, down from 588,898,000 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 485,396,000 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 11,223,600 hectares (ha).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest, 44% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 30% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] For 2015, 56% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership and 44% private ownership.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Many regions have starkly different microclimates.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] An equatorial climate characterizes much of northern Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] There is no real dry season, but there are some variations in the period of the year when most rain falls.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Temperatures average 25 °C (77 °F), with more significant temperature variation between night and day than between seasons.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Over central Brazil, rainfall is more seasonal, characteristic of a savanna climate.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] This region is as extensive as the Amazon basin but has a very different climate as it lies farther south at a higher altitude.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In the interior northeast, seasonal rainfall is even more extreme.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] South of Bahia, near the coasts, and more southerly most of the state of São Paulo, the distribution of rainfall changes, with rain falling throughout the year.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The south enjoys subtropical conditions, with cool winters and average annual temperatures not exceeding 18 °C (64.4 °F); winter frosts and snowfall are not rare in the highest areas.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The semiarid climatic region generally receives less than 800 millimeters (31.5 in) of rain, most of which generally falls in a period of three to five months of the year and occasionally less than this, creating long periods of drought.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil's 1877–78 *Grande Seca* (Great Drought), the worst in Brazil's history, caused approximately half a million deaths.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] A similarly devastating drought occurred in 1915.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In 2024, for the first time, "a drought has covered all the way from the North to the country's Southeast".
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] It is the strongest drought in Brazil since the beginning of measurement in the 1950s, covering almost 60% of the country's territory.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The drought is linked to deforestation and climate change.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Climate change in Brazil is causing higher temperatures and longer-lasting heatwaves, changing precipitation patterns, more intense wildfires and heightened fire risk.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil's hydropower, agriculture and urban water supplies will be affected.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil's rainforests, and the Amazon, are particularly at risk to climate change.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] At worst, large areas of the Amazon River basin could turn into savannah, with severe consequences for global climate and local livelihoods.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Extreme weather events like droughts and flash floods are causing annual losses of around R$13 billion (US$2.6 billion), equivalent to 0.1% of the country's 2022 GDP.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Climate impacts could exacerbate poverty.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil's greenhouse gas emissions per person are higher than the global average, and Brazil is among the top 10 highest emitting countries.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Greenhouse gas emissions by Brazil are over 4% of the annual world total.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In 2026 the Brazilian government has launched a National Climate Change Plan which should cut greenhouse gas emissions by 59% - 67% by 2035, and make the country carbon neutral by 2050.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil hosted the 2025 United Nations Climate Change Conference, in which it launched the Global carbon market coalition immediately joined by 11 countries including Brazil, China, the European Union, United Kingdom.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] According to some calculations, a global carbon market can speed up emission reduction seven-fold.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazilian topography is also diverse and includes hills, mountains, plains, highlands, and scrublands.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Much of the terrain lies between 200 meters (660 ft) and 800 meters (2,600 ft) in elevation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The main upland area occupies most of the southern half of the country.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The northwestern parts of the plateau consist of broad, rolling terrain broken by low, rounded hills.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The southeastern section is more rugged, with a complex mass of ridges and mountain ranges reaching elevations of up to 1,200 meters (3,900 ft).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] These ranges include the Mantiqueira and Espinhaço mountains and the Serra do Mar.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In the north, the Guiana Highlands form a major drainage divide, separating rivers that flow south into the Amazon Basin from rivers that empty into the Orinoco River system, in Venezuela, to the north.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The highest point in Brazil is the Pico da Neblina at 2,994 meters (9,823 ft), and the lowest is the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil has a dense and complex system of rivers, one of the world's most extensive, with eight major drainage basins, all of which drain into the Atlantic.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Major rivers include the Amazon (the world's largest in terms of water volume), the Paraná and its major tributary the Iguaçu (which includes the Iguazu Falls), the Negro, São Francisco, Xingu, Madeira and Tapajós rivers.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The wildlife of Brazil comprises all naturally occurring animals, plants, and fungi in the South American country.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Home to 60% of the Amazon rainforest, which accounts for approximately one-tenth of all species in the world, Brazil is considered to have the greatest biodiversity of any country on the planet, containing over 70% of all animal and plant species catalogued.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil has the most known species of plants (55,000), freshwater fish (3,000) and mammals (over 689).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] It also ranks third on the list of countries with the most bird species (1,832) and second with the most reptile species (744).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The number of fungal species is unknown but is large.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil is second only to Indonesia as the country with the most endemic species.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil's large territory comprises different ecosystems, such as the Amazon rainforest, recognized as having the greatest biological diversity in the world, with the Atlantic Forest and the Cerrado sustaining the greatest biodiversity.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In the south, the Araucaria moist forests grow under temperate conditions.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The rich wildlife of Brazil reflects the variety of natural habitats.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Scientists estimate that the total number of plant and animal species in Brazil could approach four million, mostly invertebrates.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Larger mammals include carnivores pumas, jaguars, ocelots, rare bush dogs, and foxes, and herbivores peccaries, tapirs, anteaters, sloths, opossums and armadillos.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Deer are plentiful in the south, and many species of New World monkeys are found in the northern rainforests.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] More than one-fifth of the Amazon rainforest in Brazil has been completely destroyed, and more than 70 mammals are endangered.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The threat of extinction comes from several sources, including deforestation and poaching.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Extinction is even more problematic in the Atlantic Forest, where nearly 93% of the forest has been cleared.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Of the 202 endangered animals in Brazil, 171 are in the Atlantic Forest.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The Amazon rainforest has been under direct threat of deforestation since the 1970s because of rapid economic and demographic expansion.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Extensive legal and illegal logging destroy forests the size of a small country per year, and with it a diverse series of species through habitat destruction and habitat fragmentation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Since 1970, over 600,000 square kilometers (230,000 sq mi) of the Amazon rainforest have been cleared by logging.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In 2017, preserved native vegetation occupied 61% of the Brazilian territory.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Agriculture occupied only 8% of the national territory and pastures 19.7%.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] For comparison, in 2019, although 43% of the entire European continent has forests, only 3% of the total forest area in Europe is of native forest.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil has a strong interest in conservation, as its agriculture sector directly depends on its forests.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The form of government is a democratic federative republic, with a presidential system, as decided in a 1993 referendum.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The president is both head of state and head of government of the Union and is elected for a four-year term, with the possibility of re-election for a second successive term.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The current president is Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The president appoints the Ministers of State, who form the cabinet and assist in government.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Legislative houses in each political entity are the main source of law in Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The National Congress is the federation's bicameral legislature, consisting of the Chamber of Deputies and the Federal Senate.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The Senate represents the 26 states and the Federal District.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Each state and the Federal District has a representation of three senators, who are elected by popular ballot for a term of eight years.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The Chamber of Deputies represents the people of each state, and its members are elected for a four-year term by a system of proportional representation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Judiciary authorities exercise jurisdictional duties almost exclusively.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] According to International IDEA's Global State of Democracy (GSoD) Indices and Democracy Tracker, Brazil performs in the mid to high range on overall democratic measures, with particular strengths in inclusive suffrage, freedom of religion, and civic engagement.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In 2021, the Economist Intelligence Unit's Democracy Index categorized Brazil as a "flawed democracy", ranking 46th in the report, and Freedom House classified it as a free country at *Freedom in the World* report.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] According to the Regimes of the World classification Brazil was an electoral democracy in year 2024.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The political-administrative organization of the Federative Republic of Brazil comprises the Union, the states, the Federal District, and the municipalities.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The Union, the states, the Federal District, and the municipalities, are the "spheres of government".
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The federation is set on five fundamental principles: sovereignty, citizenship, dignity of human beings, the social values of labor and freedom of enterprise, and political pluralism.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The classic tripartite branches of government (executive, legislative and judicial under a checks and balances system) are formally established by the constitution.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The executive and legislative are organized independently in all three spheres of government, while the judiciary is organized only at the federal and state and Federal District spheres.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] All members of the executive and legislative branches are directly elected.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] For most of its democratic history, Brazil has had a multi-party system, with proportional representation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Voting is compulsory for the literate between 18 and 70 years old and optional for illiterates and those between 16 and 18 or beyond 70.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The country has around 30 registered political parties.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Twenty political parties are represented in Congress.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] It is common for politicians to switch parties, and thus the proportion of congressional seats held by particular parties changes regularly.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazilian law is based on the civil law legal system and civil law concepts prevail over common law practice.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Most of Brazilian law is codified, although non-codified statutes also represent a substantial part, playing a complementary role.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Court decisions set out interpretive guidelines; however, they are seldom binding on other specific cases.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Doctrinal works and the works of academic jurists have strong influence in law creation and in law cases.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Judges and other judicial officials are appointed after passing entry exams.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The legal system is based on the Federal Constitution, promulgated on 5 October 1988, and the fundamental law of Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] All other legislation and court decisions must conform to its rules.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] As of July 2022, there have been 124 amendments.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The highest court is the Supreme Federal Court.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] States have their own constitutions, which must not contradict the Federal Constitution.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Municipalities and the Federal District have "organic laws" (*leis orgânicas*), which act in a similar way to constitutions.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Legislative entities are the main source of statutes, although in certain matters judiciary and executive bodies may enact legal norms.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Jurisdiction is administered by the judiciary entities, although in rare situations the Federal Constitution allows the Federal Senate to pass on legal judgments.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] There are also specialized military, labor and electoral courts.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil is a federation composed of 26 states, one federal district, and the 5,571 municipalities.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] States have autonomous administrations, collect their own taxes and receive a share of taxes collected by the Federal government.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] They have a governor and a unicameral legislative body elected directly by their voters.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] They also have independent Courts of Law for common justice.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] States have the ability to create their own laws and establish their own constitutions but criminal and civil laws can be voted by only the federal bicameral Congress and are uniform throughout the country.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Municipalities, as the states, have autonomous administrations, collect their own taxes and receive a share of taxes collected by the federal and state government.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Each has an elected mayor and legislative body, but no separate Court of Law.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Indeed, a Court of Law organized by the state can encompass many municipalities in a single justice administrative division called *comarca*.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil's constitution also provides for the creation of federal territories, which are administrative divisions directly controlled by the federal government.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] However, there are currently no federal territories in the country, as the 1988 constitution abolished the last three: Amapá and Roraima (which gained statehood) and Fernando de Noronha, which became a state district of Pernambuco.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] According to the constitution, the president has ultimate authority over foreign policy, while Congress is tasked with reviewing and considering all diplomatic nominations and international treaties, as well as legislation relating to Brazilian foreign policy.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil's foreign policy is a by-product of the country's position as a regional power in Latin America, a leader among developing countries, and an emerging world power.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazilian foreign policy has generally been based on the principles of multilateralism, peaceful dispute settlement, and non-intervention in the affairs of other countries.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil is a founding member state of the Community of Portuguese Language Countries (CPLP), also known as the Lusophone Commonwealth, an international organization and political association of Lusophone nations.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] An increasingly well-developed tool of Brazil's foreign policy is providing aid as a donor to other developing countries.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil does not just use its growing economic strength to provide financial aid, but it also provides high levels of expertise and most importantly of all, a quiet non-confrontational diplomacy to improve governance levels.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Total aid is estimated to be around $1 billion per year.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In addition, Brazil already managed a peacekeeping mission in Haiti ($350 million) and makes in-kind contributions to the World Food Programme ($300 million).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The scale of this aid places it on par with China and India.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The Brazilian South-South aid has been described as a "global model in waiting".
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The armed forces of Brazil are the largest in Latin America by active personnel and the largest in terms of military equipment.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] It consists of the Brazilian Army (including the Army Aviation Command), the Brazilian Navy (including the Marine Corps and Naval Aviation) and the Brazilian Air Force.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil's conscription policy gives it one of the world's largest military forces, estimated at more than 1.6 million reservists annually.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The Air Force is the largest in Latin America and has about 700 crewed aircraft in service and effective about 67,000 personnel.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Numbering close to 236,000 active personnel, the Brazilian Army has the largest number of armored vehicles in South America, including armored transports and tanks.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The states' Military Police and the Military Firefighters Corps are designated as auxiliary forces of the army by the constitution, but are under the control of each state's governor.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil's navy once operated some of the most powerful warships in the world with the two *Minas Geraes*-class dreadnoughts, sparking a naval arms race between Argentina, Brazil, and Chile.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Today, it is a green water force and has a group of specialized elite in retaking ships and naval facilities, GRUMEC, unit specially trained to protect Brazilian oil platforms along its coast.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] As of 2022, it is the only navy in Latin America that operates a helicopter carrier, NAM *Atlântico* and one of twelve navies in the world to operate or have one under construction.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In Brazil, the constitution establishes six different police agencies for law enforcement: Federal Police Department, Federal Highway Police, Federal Railroad Police, Federal, District and State Penal Police (included by the Constitutional Amendment No.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] 104, of 2019), Military Police and Civil Police.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Of these, the former three are affiliated with federal authorities, the latter two are subordinate to state governments and the Penal Police can be subordinated to the federal or state/district government.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] All police forces are overseen by the executive branch of the federal or state governments.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The National Public Security Force also can act in public disorder situations arising anywhere in the country.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The country has high levels of violent crime, such as gun violence and homicides.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] In 2022, the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime (UNODC) estimated an intentional homicide rate of 21.1 per 100,000 inhabitants.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The number considered acceptable by the World Health Organization (WHO) is about 10 homicides per 100,000 inhabitants.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] While in São Paulo the homicide rate registered in 2025 was 5.4 per 100,000 inhabitants, in Ceará it was 32.6 per 100,000 inhabitants.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The national homicide rate for 2025 was 16 per 100,000 inhabitants, the lowest in over a decade.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Brazil also has high levels of incarceration.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] It had the third largest prison population in the world of approximately 909,067 prisoners in 2024, which put it only behind the United States (1,808,100) and China (1,690,000).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The high number of prisoners eventually overloaded the Brazilian prison system, leading to a shortfall of about 200,000 accommodations.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Human rights in Brazil include the right to life and freedom of speech; and condemnation of slavery and torture.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The nation ratified the American Convention on Human Rights.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] The 2017 Freedom in the World report by Freedom House gives Brazil a score of "2" for both political rights and civil liberties; "1" represents the most free, and "7", the least.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] According to UNESCO, "Brazil promotes a vast array of actions for the advancement and defense of human rights, even though it faces enormous social and economic inequalities".
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p01] Same-sex couples in Brazil have held nationwide marriage rights since May 2013.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil is a developing country with an upper-middle income mixed market economy that is rich in natural resources.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] It has the largest national economy in Latin America, the tenth largest economy in the world by nominal GDP, and the eighth largest by PPP.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] After rapid growth in preceding decades, Brazil entered a recession in 2014 amid a political corruption scandal and nationwide protests; in 2024, the economy began showing consistent significant growth.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil has a labor force of roughly 100 million, which is the world's fifth largest.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Its foreign exchange reserves are the tenth-highest in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The B3 in São Paulo is the largest stock exchange of Latin America by market capitalization.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Roughly one-fifth of Brazilians live in poverty: about 3.8% of the total population lives at $3.00 a day, while about 23% live at $8.30 a day.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil's economy suffers from endemic corruption and high income inequality.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The Brazilian real is the national currency.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil's diversified economy includes agriculture, industry and a wide range of services.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The large service sector accounts for about 72.7% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (20.7%), while the agriculture sector is by far the smallest, making up 6.6% of total GDP.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil is one of the largest producers of various agricultural commodities, and also has a large cooperative sector that provides 50% of the food in the country.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Regarding livestock, it is one of the five largest producers of chicken meat, beef, pork and cow's milk in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In the mining sector, Brazil is among the largest producers of iron ore, copper, gold, bauxite, manganese, tin, niobium, and nickel.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In terms of precious stones, Brazil is the world's largest producer of amethyst, topaz, agate and one of the main producers of tourmaline, emerald, aquamarine, garnet and opal.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The country is a major exporter of soy, iron ore, pulp (cellulose), maize, beef, chicken meat, soybean meal, sugar, coffee, tobacco, cotton, orange juice, footwear, airplanes, cars, vehicle parts, gold, ethanol and semi-finished iron, among other products.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil is the world's 24th-largest exporter and 26th-largest importer as of 2021.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] China is its largest trading partner, accounting for 32% of the total trade.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Other large trading partners include the United States, Argentina, the Netherlands and Canada.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Its automotive industry is the eighth-largest in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In the food industry, Brazil was the second-largest exporter of processed foods in the world in 2019.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The country was the second-largest producer of pulp in the world and the eighth-largest producer of paper in 2016.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In the footwear industry, Brazil was the fourth-largest producer in 2019.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] It was also the ninth-largest producer of steel in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In 2018, the chemical industry of Brazil was the eighth-largest in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Although it was among the five largest world producers in 2013, Brazil's textile industry is very little integrated into world trade.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The tertiary sector (trade and services) represented 75.8% of the country's GDP in 2018, according to the IBGE.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The service sector was responsible for 60% of GDP and trade for 13%.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] It covers commerce, transport, education, social and health services, research and development, sports activities, etc.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Micro and small businesses represent 30% of the country's GDP.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In the commercial sector they represent 53% of the GDP within the activities of the sector.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Natural areas are its most popular tourism product, a combination of ecotourism with leisure and recreation, mainly sun and beach, and adventure travel, as well as cultural tourism.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Among the most popular destinations are the Amazon Rainforest, beaches and dunes in the Northeast Region, the Pantanal in the Center-West Region, beaches at Rio de Janeiro and Santa Catarina, cultural tourism in Minas Gerais and business trips to São Paulo.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Domestic tourism is a key market segment for the tourism industry in Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In 2005, 51 million Brazilian nationals made ten times more trips than foreign tourists and spent five times more money than their international counterparts.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The main destination states in 2023 were São Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, and Rio Grande do Sul.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The main source of tourists for the entire country is São Paulo state.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In terms of tourism revenues, the top earners by state were São Paulo and Bahia.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] For 2005, the three main trip purposes were visiting friends and family (53.1%), sun and beach (40.8%), and cultural tourism (12.5%).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Technological research in Brazil is largely carried out in public universities and research institutes, with the majority of funding for basic research coming from various government agencies.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil's most esteemed technological hubs are the Oswaldo Cruz Institute, the Butantan Institute, the Air Force's Aerospace Technical Center, the Brazilian Agricultural Research Corporation and the National Institute for Space Research.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The Brazilian Space Agency has the most developed space program in Latin America, with significant capabilities in launch vehicles, launch sites, and satellite manufacturing.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil is the only country in the Southern Hemisphere involved in the International Space Station (ISS).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The country also develops submarines and is the world's third largest aircraft producer, primarily through Embraer.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The country is also a pioneer in the search for oil in deep water, from where it extracts 73% of its reserves.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Uranium is enriched at the Resende Nuclear Fuel Factory, mostly for research purposes (as Brazil obtains 88% of its electricity from hydroelectricity), and the country's first nuclear submarine is expected to launch in 2029.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil is one of the three countries in Latin America with an operational Synchrotron Laboratory (a research facility on physics, chemistry, material science and life sciences), and the only Latin American country with a domestic fabrication plant, the CEITEC.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] According to the Global Information Technology Report 2009–2010 of the World Economic Forum, Brazil is the world's 61st largest developer of information technology.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil ranked 52nd in the Global Innovation Index in 2025, up from 66th in 2019.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Among the most renowned Brazilian inventors are priests Bartolomeu de Gusmão, Landell de Moura and Francisco João de Azevedo, besides Alberto Santos-Dumont, Evaristo Conrado Engelberg, Manuel Dias de Abreu, Andreas Pavel and Nélio José Nicolai.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil is the world's eleventh-largest energy consumer.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Much of its energy comes from renewable sources, particularly hydroelectricity and ethanol; the Itaipu Dam is the world's largest hydroelectric plant by energy generation, and the country has other large plants such as Belo Monte and Tucuruí.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The first car with an ethanol engine was produced in 1978 and the first airplane engine running on ethanol in 2005.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] At the end of 2021, Brazil ranked second in the world by installed hydroelectric power (109.4 GW) and biomass (15.8 GW), seventh in installed wind power (21.1 GW) and 14th in installed solar power (13.0 GW)—on track to also become one of the top 10 in the world in solar energy.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] At the end of 2024, Brazil was the fourth largest producer of wind energy in the world (107.8 TWh), behind only China, the United States and Germany, and the world's fifth largest producer of solar energy (74.7 TWh).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Overall, Brazil ranks third globally in renewable electricity production, after China and the United States, accounting for 7% of the global total.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The Brazilian energy matrix is characterized by a higher degree of renewable energy than the global average; in 2022, the world energy matrix was only 14% renewable energy, compared to 45% in Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Petroleum and oil products made up 34.3% of the country's matrix; sugar cane derivatives, 18%; hydraulic energy, 12.4%; natural gas, 12.2%; firewood and charcoal, 8.8%; varied renewable energies, 7%; mineral coal, 5.3%; nuclear, 1.4%, and other non-renewable energies, 0.6%.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Similarly, the vast majority of Brazilian electricity is derived from renewable sources: 83% compared to 25% worldwide.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The leading sources are hydraulic energy at 64.9%; biomass, 8.4%; wind, 8.6%; solar, 1%; natural gas, 9.3%; oil products, 2%; nuclear, 2.5%; and coal and derivatives, 3.3%.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil has the largest electricity sector in Latin America; its capacity at the end of 2021 was 181,532 MW.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The Brazilian government has embarked on a program over the decades to reduce dependence on imported oil, which previously accounted for more than 70% of the country's oil needs.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil became self-sufficient in oil in 2006–2007.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] By the end of 2021, the country was the seventh largest oil producer in the world, with an average of nearly three million barrels per day, and became an exporter of the product.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazilian roads are the primary carriers of freight and passenger traffic.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The road system totaled 2,000,000 km (1,242,742 mi) in 2023, ranking fourth largest by size globally.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil's railway system has been declining since 1945, when emphasis shifted to highway construction.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The country's total railway track length was 30,576 km (18,999 mi) in 2015, as compared with 31,848 km (19,789 mi) in 1970, making it the ninth largest network in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Most of the railway system belonged to the Federal Railroad Network Corporation (RFFSA), which was privatized in 2007.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The São Paulo Metro began operating on 14 September 1974 as the first underground transit system in Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] There are over 4,900 airports and airfields in Brazil, second only to the United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] São Paulo–Guarulhos International Airport, near São Paulo, is the largest and busiest airport with nearly 43 million passengers annually, while handling the vast majority of commercial traffic for the country.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] For freight transport, waterways are of importance.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The industrial zones of Manaus can be reached only by means of the Solimões–Amazonas waterway (3,250 kilometers or 2,020 miles in length, with a minimum depth of six meters or 20 feet).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The country also has 50,000 kilometers (31,000 miles) of waterways.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Coastal shipping links widely separated parts of the country.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Bolivia and Paraguay have been given free ports at Santos.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Of the 36 deep-water ports, Santos, Itajaí, Rio Grande, Paranaguá, Rio de Janeiro, Sepetiba, Vitória, Suape, Manaus and São Francisco do Sul are the most important.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Bulk carriers have to wait up to 18 days before being serviced; container ships take 36.3 hours on average.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] According to the latest official projection, Brazil's estimated population was 213,421,037 on 1 July 2025—an increase from the figure of 203 million reported by the 2022 census.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The population of Brazil, as recorded by the 2008 PNAD, was approximately 190 million (22.31 inhabitants per square kilometer or 57.8/sq mi), with a ratio of men to women of 0.95:1 and 83.75% of the population defined as urban.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The population is heavily concentrated in the Southeast (89 million inhabitants) and Northeast (54.6 million inhabitants), while the two most extensive regions, the Center-West and the North, which together make up 64.12% of Brazilian territory, have a total of only 33.8 million inhabitants.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The first census in Brazil was carried out in 1872 and recorded a population of 9,930,478.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] From 1880 to 1930, four million Europeans arrived.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil's population increased significantly between 1940 and 1970, because of a decline in the mortality rate, even though the birth rate underwent a slight decline.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In the 1940s the annual population growth rate was 2.4%, rising to 3.0% in the 1950s and remaining at 2.9% in the 1960s, as life expectancy rose from 44 to 54 years and to 72.6 years in 2007.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] It has been steadily falling since the 1960s, from 3.04% per year between 1950 and 1960 to 1.05% in 2008 and is expected to fall to a negative value of –0.29% by 2050 thus completing the demographic transition.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In 2022, the illiteracy rate was roughly 7%, a significant decline from 11.48% in 2008.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] By comparison, in 1940, more than half the population (54%) was illiterate.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] According to IBGE (Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics) urban areas already concentrate 84.35% of the population, while the Southeast region remains the most populated one, with over 80 million inhabitants.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The largest urban agglomerations in Brazil are São Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, and Belo Horizonte—all in the Southeastern Region—with 21.1, 12.3, and 5.1 million inhabitants respectively.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The majority of state capitals are the largest cities in their states, except for Vitória, the capital of Espírito Santo, and Florianópolis, the capital of Santa Catarina.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] From the 19th century, Brazil opened its borders to immigration.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] About five million people from over 60 countries migrated to Brazil between 1808 and 1972, most of them of Portuguese, Italian, Spanish, German, English, Ukrainian, Polish, Jewish, African, Armenian, Russian, Chinese, Japanese, Korean and Arab origin.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil has the second-largest Jewish community in Latin America after Argentina making up 0.06% of its population.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Outside of the Arab world, Brazil also has the largest population of Arab ancestry in the world, with 15–20 million people.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] According to Brazil's Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Brazil is home to a Lebanese diaspora of 7-10 million, surpassing the population of Lebanese individuals residing in Lebanon.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazilian society is more markedly divided by social class lines, although a high income disparity is found between race groups, so racism and classism often overlap.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Higher percents of Blacks, mulattoes and tri-racials can be found in the eastern coast of the Northeastern region from Bahia to Paraíba and also in northern Maranhão, southern Minas Gerais and eastern Rio de Janeiro.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] People of considerable Amerindian ancestry form the majority of the population in the Northern, Northeastern and Center-Western regions.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In 2007, the National Indian Foundation estimated that Brazil has 67 different uncontacted tribes, up from their estimate of 40 in 2005.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil is believed to have the largest number of uncontacted peoples in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The official language of Brazil is Portuguese (Article 13 of the Constitution of the Federal Republic of Brazil), which almost all of the population speaks and is virtually the only language used in newspapers, radio, television, and for business and administrative purposes.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil is the only Portuguese-speaking nation in the Americas, making the language an important part of Brazilian national identity and giving it a national culture distinct from those of its Spanish-speaking neighbors.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] These differences are comparable to those between American and British English.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] LIBRAS teachers, instructors and translators are recognized professionals.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Schools and health services must provide access ("inclusion") to deaf people.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Minority languages are spoken throughout the nation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] One hundred and eighty Amerindian languages are spoken in remote areas and a significant number of other languages are spoken by immigrants and their descendants.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In the municipality of São Gabriel da Cachoeira, Nheengatu (a currently endangered creole language that, together with its southern relative língua geral paulista, once was a major lingua franca in Brazil), Baniwa and Tucano languages had been granted co-official status with Portuguese.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Talian is officially a historic heritage of Rio Grande do Sul, and two German dialects possess co-official status in a few municipalities.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Italian is also recognized as "ethnic language" in Santa Teresa and Vila Velha, in the state of Espírito Santo.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Christianity is the country's predominant faith, with Catholicism being its largest denomination.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil has the world's largest Catholic population.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] According to the 2022 demographic census (the PNAD survey does not inquire about religion), 56.75% of the population followed Catholicism; 26.85% Protestantism; 1.84% Kardecist spiritism; 5.06% other religions, undeclared or undetermined; while 9.28% had no religion.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Religious diversity in Brazil developed from the meeting of the Catholic Church with the religious traditions of enslaved African peoples and indigenous peoples.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] This confluence of faiths during the Portuguese colonization of Brazil led to the development of a diverse array of syncretistic practices within the overarching umbrella of Brazilian Catholic Church, characterized by traditional Portuguese festivities.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Religious pluralism increased during the 20th century, and the Protestant community had grown to include over 22% of the population by 2010—partly due to a mixture of American missionary and US government influence.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The most common Protestant denominations are Evangelical Pentecostal ones.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Other Protestant branches with a notable presence in the country include the Baptists, Seventh-day Adventists, Lutherans and the Reformed tradition.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In recent decades, Protestantism, particularly in forms of Pentecostalism and Evangelicalism, has spread in Brazil, while the proportion of Catholics had dropped significantly during the 2010s.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] As they have spread throughout Brazil, many have even been deeply involved in Brazilian and international politics, and Evangelical Protestant influence has been implicated in the 2022 Brazilian coup plot.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Since 2022, Evangelicals and Catholics have begun reconsidering religion as a political factor; however as of 2025, several Evangelical denominations have continued considering its influence in politics.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] After Protestantism, individuals professing no religion are also a significant group, having exceeded 8% of the population according to the 2010 census.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The cities of Boa Vista, Salvador, and Porto Velho have the greatest proportion of Irreligious residents in Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Teresina, Fortaleza, and Florianópolis were the most Roman Catholic in the country.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Greater Rio de Janeiro, not including the city proper, is the most irreligious and least Roman Catholic Brazilian periphery, while Greater Porto Alegre and Greater Fortaleza are on the opposite sides of the lists, respectively.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In October 2009, the Brazilian Senate approved, and enacted by the President of Brazil in February 2010, an agreement with the Vatican, in which the Legal Statute of the Catholic Church in Brazil is recognized.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The Federal Constitution and the Law of Guidelines and Bases of National Education determine that the union, the states, the Federal District and the municipalities must manage and organize their respective education systems.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Each of these public educational systems is responsible for its own maintenance, which manages funds as well as the mechanisms and funding sources.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The constitution reserves 25% of the state budget and 18% of federal taxes and municipal taxes for education.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Illiteracy is higher in the Northeast, where 13.87% of the population is illiterate, while the South, has 3.3% illiteracy.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil's private institutions tend to be more exclusive and offer better quality education, so many high-income families send their children there.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The result is a segregated educational system that reflects extreme income disparities and reinforces social inequality.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] However, efforts to change this are making impacts.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The University of São Paulo is often considered the best in Brazil and Latin America.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Of the top 20 Latin American universities, eight are Brazilian; most are public.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Attending an institution of higher education is required by Law of Guidelines and Bases of Education.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Kindergarten, elementary and medium education are required of all students.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The Brazilian public health system, the Unified Health System (*Sistema Único de Saúde* – SUS), is managed and provided by all levels of government, being the largest system of this type in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] On the other hand, private healthcare systems play a complementary role.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Public health services are universal and offered to all citizens of the country for free.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] However, the construction and maintenance of health centers and hospitals are financed by taxes, and the country spends about 9% of its GDP on expenditures in the area.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In 2021, Brazil had 2.1 doctors and 2.5 hospital beds for every 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Despite all the progress made since the creation of the universal health care system in 1988, there are still several public health issues in Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In 2023, infant (2.51%) and maternal mortality rates (197.3 deaths per 100,000 births) were still high.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The number of deaths from noncommunicable diseases, such as cardiovascular diseases (151.7 deaths per 100,000 inhabitants) and cancer (72.7 deaths per 100,000 inhabitants), also has a considerable impact on the health of the Brazilian population.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Finally, external but preventable factors such as car accidents, violence and suicide caused 14.9% of all deaths in the country.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The Brazilian health system was ranked 125th among the 191 countries evaluated by the World Health Organization (WHO) in 2000.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The core culture of Brazil is derived from Portuguese culture, due to its strong colonial ties with the Portuguese Empire.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Among other influences, the Portuguese introduced the Portuguese language, Roman Catholicism and colonial architectural styles.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazilian culture was also strongly influenced by African, indigenous and non-Portuguese European cultures and traditions.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Some aspects of Brazilian culture were influenced by the contributions of Italian, German and other European as well as Japanese, Jewish and Arab immigrants who arrived in large numbers in the South and Southeast of Brazil during the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The indigenous Amerindians influenced Brazil's language and cuisine; and the Africans influenced language, cuisine, music, dance and religion.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazilian art has developed since the 16th century into different styles that range from Baroque (the dominant style in Brazil until the early 19th century) to Romanticism, Modernism, Expressionism, Cubism, Surrealism and Abstractionism.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazilian cinema dates back to the birth of the medium in the late 19th century and has gained a new level of international acclaim since the 1960s.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The architecture of Brazil is influenced by Europe, especially Portugal.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] It has a history that goes back 500 years to the time, when Pedro Álvares Cabral landed in Brazil in 1500.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Portuguese colonial architecture was the first wave of architecture to go to Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] It is the basis for all Brazilian architecture of later centuries.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In the 19th century, during the time of the Empire of Brazil, the country followed European trends and adopted Neoclassical and Gothic Revival architecture.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Then, in the 20th century, especially in Brasília, Brazil experimented with modernist architecture.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The colonial architecture of Brazil dates to the early 16th century, when Brazil was first explored, conquered and settled by the Portuguese.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The Portuguese built architecture familiar to them in Europe in their aim to colonize Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] They built Portuguese colonial architecture, which included churches and civic architecture, including houses and forts, in Brazilian cities and the countryside.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] During the 19th century, Brazilian architecture saw the introduction of more European styles to Brazil, such as Neoclassical and Gothic Revival architecture.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] This was usually mixed with Brazilian influences from their own heritage.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In the 1950s modernist architecture was introduced when Brasília was built as a new federal capital in the interior of Brazil to help develop the interior.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The architect Oscar Niemeyer idealized and built government buildings, churches and civic buildings in the modernist style.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazilian painting emerged in the late 16th century, influenced by Baroque, Rococo, Neoclassicism, Romanticism, Realism, Modernism, Expressionism, Surrealism, Cubism and Abstracionism making it a major art style called Brazilian academic art.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Upon the creation of the Imperial Academy of Fine Arts, new artistic movements spread across the country during the 19th century and later the event called Modern Art Week broke with academic tradition in 1922 and started a nationalist trend which was influenced by modernist arts.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The music of Brazil was formed mainly from the fusion of European, Native Indigenous, and African elements.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Until the nineteenth century, Portugal was the gateway to most of the influences that built Brazilian music, although many of these elements were not of Portuguese origin, but generally European.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The first was José Maurício Nunes Garcia, author of sacred pieces with an influence of Viennese classicism.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The major contribution of the African element was the rhythmic diversity and some dances and instruments.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Popular music since the late eighteenth century, samba was considered the most typical and on the UNESCO cultural heritage list.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Samba-reggae, Axé, Maracatu, Frevo and Afoxê are four music traditions that have been popularized by their appearance in the annual Brazilian Carnivals.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Capoeira is usually played with its own music referred to as capoeira music, which is usually considered to be a call-and-response type of folk music.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Forró is a type of folk music prominent during the Festa Junina in northeastern Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Draper III, a professor of Portuguese at the University of Missouri, argues that Forró was used as a way to subdue feelings of nostalgia for a rural lifestyle.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Choro is a popular musical instrumental style.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Its origins are in 19th-century Rio de Janeiro.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The style often has a fast and happy rhythm, characterized by subtle modulations and full of syncopation and counterpoint. lambada and Carimbó achieved success in Latin music, originating from Pará.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Bossa nova is also a well-known style of Brazilian music developed and popularized in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The phrase "bossa nova" means literally 'new trend'.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] A lyrical fusion of samba and jazz, bossa nova acquired a large following starting in the 1960s.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazilian literature dates back to the 16th century, to the writings of the first Portuguese explorers in Brazil, such as Pero Vaz de Caminha, filled with descriptions of fauna, flora and commentary about the indigenous population that fascinated European readers.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil produced significant works in Romanticism—novelists such as Joaquim Manuel de Macedo and José de Alencar wrote novels about love and pain.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Alencar, in his long career, also treated indigenous people as heroes in the Indigenist novels *O Guarani*, *Iracema* and *Ubirajara*.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Machado de Assis, one of his contemporaries, wrote in virtually all genres and continues to gain international prestige from critics worldwide.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil's most significant literary award is the Camões Prize, which it shares with the rest of the Portuguese-speaking world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] As of 2016, Brazil has eleven recipients of the prize.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil also holds its own literary academy, the Brazilian Academy of Letters, a non-profit cultural organization aimed at perpetuating the care of the national language and literature.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The theatre in Brazil has its origins in the period of Jesuit expansion, when theater was used for the dissemination of Catholic doctrine in the 16th century.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In the 17th and 18th centuries, dramatists on the scene of European derivation were for court or private performances.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] During the 19th century, the playwrights Antônio Gonçalves Dias and Luís Carlos Martins Pena were known for their performance.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] There were also numerous operas and orchestras.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The Brazilian conductor Antônio Carlos Gomes became internationally known with operas such as *Il Guarany*.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] At the end of the 19th century, orchestrated dramaturgias were accompanied with songs of famous artists such as the conductress Chiquinha Gonzaga.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Already in the early 20th century there was the presence of theaters, entrepreneurs and actor companies.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In 1940, Paschoal Carlos Magno and his student's theater, the comedians group and the Italian actors Adolfo Celi, Ruggero Jacobbi and Aldo Calvo, founders of the *Teatro Brasileiro de Comédia*, renewed the Brazilian theater.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] From the 1960s, it was attended by a theater dedicated to social and religious issues.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The most prominent authors at this stage were Jorge Andrade and Ariano Suassuna.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The Brazilian film industry began in the late 19th century, during the early days of the Belle Époque.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] While there were national film productions during the early 20th century, American films such as *Rio the Magnificent* were made in Rio de Janeiro to promote tourism in the city.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The films *Limite* (1931) and *Ganga Bruta* (1933), the latter being produced by Adhemar Gonzaga through the prolific studio Cinédia, were poorly received at release and failed at the box office, but are acclaimed nowadays and placed among the finest Brazilian films of all time.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The 1941 unfinished film *It's All True* was divided into four segments, two of which were filmed in Brazil and directed by Orson Welles; it was originally produced as part of the United States' Good Neighbor Policy during Getúlio Vargas' Estado Novo.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] During the 1960s, the Cinema Novo movement rose to prominence with directors such as Glauber Rocha, Nelson Pereira dos Santos, Paulo César Saraceni and Arnaldo Jabor.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Glauber Rocha's films *Black God, White Devil* (1964) and *Entranced Earth* (1967) are considered to be some of the greatest and most influential in Brazilian film history.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Rocha won the Best Director Award at the 1969 Cannes Film Festival for *Antonio das Mortes* and the 1977 Special Jury Prize for Best Short Film for *Di*.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The 2002 crime film *City of God*, directed by Fernando Meirelles, was critically acclaimed, scoring 90% on Rotten Tomatoes, being placed in Roger Ebert's Best Films of the Decade list and receiving four Academy Award nominations in 2004, including Best Director.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Notable film festivals in Brazil include the São Paulo and Rio de Janeiro International Film Festivals and the Gramado Festival.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The film *I'm Still Here*, directed by Walter Salles, was nominated for Best Actress (Torres) and Best Picture at the 97th Academy Awards, and won Best International Feature Film, becoming the first-ever Brazilian produced film to win an Academy Award.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The film *The Secret Agent* had its world premiere at the main competition of the 2025 Cannes Film Festival on 18 May 2025, where it won the Best Actor prize for Wagner Moura, the Best Director prize for Mendonça and the FIPRESCI Prize.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] It received further widespread critical acclaim.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The Brazilian press was officially born in Rio de Janeiro on 13 May 1808 with the creation of the Royal Printing National Press by the Prince Regent John.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The *Gazeta do Rio de Janeiro*, the first newspaper published in the country, began to circulate on 10 September 1808.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The largest newspapers nowadays are *Folha de S.Paulo*, *O Globo*, and *O Estado de S.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Radio broadcasting began on 7 September 1922, with a speech by then President Epitácio Pessoa, and was formalized on 20 April 1923 with the creation of the "Radio Society of Rio de Janeiro".
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Television in Brazil began officially on 18 September 1950, with the founding of TV Tupi by Assis Chateaubriand.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Since then, television has grown in the country, creating large commercial broadcast networks such as Globo, SBT, RecordTV, Bandeirantes and RedeTV.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] By the mid-1960s, Brazilian universities had installed mainframe computers from IBM and Burroughs Large Systems.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In the 1970s and 1980s, the Brazilian government restricted foreign imports to protect the local manufacturing of computers.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In the 1980s, Brazil produced half of the computers sold in the country.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] By 2009, the mobile phone and Internet use in Brazil was the fifth largest in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] As of early 2025, internet penetration in Brazil stood at 86.2% of the total population (183 million individuals), and the ratio of cellular mobile connections to the total population was 102% (217 million active connections).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In May 2010, the Brazilian government launched TV Brasil Internacional, an international television station, initially broadcasting to 49 countries.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Commercial television channels broadcast internationally include Globo Internacional, RecordTV Internacional and Band Internacional.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazilian cuisine varies greatly by region, reflecting the country's varying mix of indigenous and immigrant populations.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] This has created a national cuisine marked by the preservation of regional differences.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Some of the most well known Brazilian foods are the feijoada, considered the country's national dish; and churrasco, a kind of barbecue which is often served in rodízio style.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Other regional foods include beijú, feijão tropeiro, vatapá, moqueca, polenta (from Italian cuisine) and acarajé (from African cuisine).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The national beverage is coffee; cachaça is Brazil's native liquor.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Cachaça is distilled from sugar cane and is the main ingredient in the national cocktail, Caipirinha.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] A typical meal consists mostly of rice and beans with beef, salad, french fries and a fried egg.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Often, it is mixed with cassava flour (farofa).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Fried potatoes, fried cassava, fried banana, fried meat and fried cheese are very often eaten in lunch and served in most typical restaurants.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil has a variety of desserts such as brigadeiros (chocolate fudge balls), bolo de rolo (roll cake with goiabada), cocada (a coconut sweet), beijinhos (coconut truffles and clove) and Romeu e Julieta (cheese with goiabada).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Peanuts are used to make paçoca, rapadura and pé de moleque.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Local common fruits such as açaí, cupuaçu, mango, papaya, cocoa, cashew, guava, orange, lime, passionfruit, pineapple, and hog plum are turned into juices and used to make chocolates, ice pops and ice cream.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The most popular sport in Brazil is football.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The Brazilian men's national team is ranked among the best in the world according to the FIFA World Rankings, and has won the World Cup tournament a record five times.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Volleyball, basketball, auto racing and martial arts also has large audiences.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The Brazil men's national volleyball team currently holds the titles of the World League, World Grand Champions Cup, World Championship and the World Cup.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In auto racing, three Brazilian drivers have won the Formula One world championship eight times.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The country has also produced significant achievements in other sports such as sailing, swimming, tennis, surfing, skateboarding, MMA, gymnastics, boxing, judo, athletics and table tennis.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Some sport variations have their origins in Brazil: beach football, futsal (indoor football) and footvolley emerged in Brazil as variations of football.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] In martial arts, Brazilians developed Capoeira, Vale tudo and Brazilian jiu-jitsu.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Brazil has hosted several high-profile international sporting events, such as the 1950 FIFA World Cup, and recently has hosted the 2014 FIFA World Cup, 2019 Copa América and 2021 Copa América.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] The São Paulo circuit, Autódromo José Carlos Pace, hosts the annual Grand Prix of Brazil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] São Paulo organized the IV Pan American Games in 1963, and Rio de Janeiro hosted the XV Pan American Games in 2007.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] On 2 October 2009, Rio de Janeiro was selected to host the 2016 Olympic Games and 2016 Paralympic Games, making it the first South American city to host the games and second in Latin America, after Mexico City.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] Furthermore, the country hosted the FIBA Basketball World Cups in 1954 and 1963.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/brazil-p02] At the 1963 event, the Brazil national basketball team won one of its two world championship titles.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago was incorporated as a city in 1837 near a portage between the Great Lakes and the Mississippi River watershed.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] It grew rapidly in the mid-19th century.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 1871, the Great Chicago Fire destroyed several square miles and left more than 100,000 homeless, but Chicago's population continued to grow.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago made noted contributions to urban planning and architecture, such as the Chicago School, the development of the City Beautiful movement, and the steel-framed skyscraper.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago is an international hub for finance, culture, commerce, industry, education, technology, telecommunications, and transportation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] It has the largest and most diverse finance derivatives market in the world, generating 20% of all volume in commodities and financial futures alone.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] O'Hare International Airport is routinely ranked among the world's top ten busiest airports by passenger traffic, and the region is also the nation's railroad hub.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The Chicago area has one of the highest gross domestic products (GDP) of any urban region in the world, ranking sixth globally, generating over $919 billion in 2024.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago's economy is diverse, with no single industry employing more than 14% of the workforce.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago is a major destination for tourism, with nearly 57 million people visiting its cultural institutions, Lake Michigan beaches, restaurants, and other tourist sites in 2025.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago's culture has made significant contributions to the visual arts, literature, film, theater, comedy (especially improvisational comedy), food, dance, and music (particularly jazz, blues, soul, hip-hop, gospel, industrial, and electronic dance music, especially house music).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago is home to the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and the Lyric Opera of Chicago, while the Art Institute of Chicago has an influential visual arts museum and art school.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The Chicago area is home to the University of Chicago, Northwestern University, and the University of Illinois Chicago, among other institutions of higher education.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] It also hosts the Barack Obama Presidential Center.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Professional sports in Chicago include all major professional leagues, including two Major League Baseball teams.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The city also hosts the Chicago Marathon, one of the World Marathon Majors.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The name *Chicago* is derived from a French rendering of the indigenous Miami–Illinois word *šikaakwa*, which was a name for a wild relative of onion and garlic known to modern botanists as *Allium tricoccum*.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The first known reference to the site of the city of Chicago as "*Checagou*" was by Robert de La Salle around 1679 in a memoir.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Henri Joutel, in his journal of 1688, noted that the eponymous wild "garlic" grew profusely in the area.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The city has had several nicknames throughout its history, such as the Windy City, Chi-Town, Second City, and City of the Big Shoulders.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In the mid-18th century, the area was inhabited by the Potawatomi, an indigenous tribe who had succeeded the Miami, Sauk and Meskwaki peoples in this region.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The first known permanent settler in Chicago was a trader, Jean Baptiste Point du Sable.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Du Sable was of African descent, perhaps born in the French colony of Saint-Domingue (Haiti), and he established the settlement in the 1780s.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] He is commonly known as the "Founder of Chicago".
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 1795, following the victory of the new United States in the Northwest Indian War, an area that was to be part of Chicago was turned over to the U.S. for a military post by native tribes in accordance with the Treaty of Greenville.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Army constructed Fort Dearborn, which was destroyed during the War of 1812 in the Battle of Fort Dearborn by the Potawatomi before being later rebuilt.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] After the War of 1812, the Odawa, Ojibwe, and Potawatomi tribes ceded additional land to the United States in the 1816 Treaty of St.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The Potawatomi were forcibly removed from their land after the 1833 Treaty of Chicago and sent west of the Mississippi River as part of the federal policy of Indian removal.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] On August 12, 1833, the Town of Chicago was organized with a population of about 200.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Within seven years it grew to more than 6,000 people.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] On June 15, 1835, the first public land sales began with Edmund Dick Taylor as Receiver of Public Monies.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The City of Chicago was incorporated on Saturday, March 4, 1837, and for several decades was the world's fastest-growing city.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] As the site of the Chicago Portage, the city became an important transportation hub between the eastern and western United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago's first railway, Galena and Chicago Union Railroad, and the Illinois and Michigan Canal opened in 1848.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The canal allowed steamboats and sailing ships on the Great Lakes to connect to the Mississippi River.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] A flourishing economy brought residents from rural communities and immigrants from abroad.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Manufacturing and retail and finance sectors became dominant, influencing the American economy.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The Chicago Board of Trade (established 1848) listed the first-ever standardized "exchange-traded" forward contracts, which were called futures contracts.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In the 1850s, Chicago gained national political prominence as the home of Senator Stephen Douglas, the champion of the Kansas–Nebraska Act and the "popular sovereignty" approach to the issue of the spread of slavery.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] These issues also helped propel another Illinoisan, Abraham Lincoln, to the national stage.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Lincoln was nominated in Chicago for U.S. president at the 1860 Republican National Convention, which was held in a purpose-built auditorium called the Wigwam.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] He defeated Douglas in the general election, and this set the stage for the American Civil War.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] To accommodate rapid population growth and demand for better sanitation, the city improved its infrastructure.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In February 1856, Chicago's Common Council approved Chesbrough's plan to build the United States' first comprehensive sewerage system.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The project raised much of central Chicago to a new grade with the use of jackscrews for raising buildings.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] While elevating Chicago, and at first improving the city's health, the untreated sewage and industrial waste now flowed into the Chicago River, and subsequently into Lake Michigan, polluting the city's primary freshwater source.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The city responded by tunneling two miles (3.2 km) out into Lake Michigan to newly built water cribs.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 1900, the problem of sewage contamination was largely resolved when the city completed a major engineering feat.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] It reversed the flow of the Chicago River so that the water flowed away from Lake Michigan rather than into it.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] This project began with the construction and improvement of the Illinois and Michigan Canal, and was completed with the Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal that connects to the Illinois River, which flows into the Mississippi River.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] On October 8, 1871, the Great Chicago Fire destroyed an area about 4 miles (6.4 km) long and 1-mile (1.6 km) wide, a large section of the city at the time.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] At least 300 people were killed and over 100,000 were left homeless from the fire.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] However, much of the city, including railroads and stockyards, survived intact, and from the ruins of the previous wooden structures arose more modern constructions of steel and stone.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] These set a precedent for worldwide construction.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] During its rebuilding period, Chicago constructed the world's first skyscraper in 1885, using steel-skeleton construction.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Labor conflicts followed the industrial boom and the rapid expansion of the labor pool during the Gilded Age, including the Haymarket affair on May 4, 1886, and in 1894 the Pullman Strike.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Anarchist and socialist groups played prominent roles in creating very large and highly organized labor actions.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Concern for social problems among Chicago's immigrant poor led Jane Addams and Ellen Gates Starr to found Hull House in 1889.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Programs that were developed there became a model for the new field of social work.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] During the 1870s and 1880s, Chicago attained national stature as the leader in the movement to improve public health.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] City laws and later, state laws that upgraded standards for the medical profession and fought urban epidemics of cholera, smallpox, and yellow fever were both passed and enforced.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] These laws became templates for public health reform in other cities and states.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The city established many large, well-landscaped municipal parks, which also included public sanitation facilities.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The chief advocate for improving public health in Chicago was John H.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Rauch established a plan for Chicago's park system in 1866.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] He created Lincoln Park by closing a cemetery filled with shallow graves, and in 1867, in response to an outbreak of cholera he helped establish a new Chicago Board of Health.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Ten years later, he became the secretary and then the president of the first Illinois State Board of Health, which carried out most of its activities in Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In the 1800s, Chicago became the nation's railroad hub, and by 1910 over 20 railroads operated passenger service out of six different downtown terminals.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 1883, Chicago's railway managers needed a general time convention, so they developed the standardized system of North American time zones.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] This system for telling time spread throughout the continent.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The desire to join the city was driven by municipal services that the city could provide its residents.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 1893, Chicago hosted the World's Columbian Exposition on former marshland at the present location of Jackson Park.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The Exposition drew 27.5 million visitors, and is considered the most influential world's fair in history.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The city's municipal device, a Y within a circle, was the result of a contest run by the *Chicago Tribune* in 1892, in anticipation of the Columbian Exposition.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The University of Chicago, formerly at another location, moved to the same South Side location in 1892.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The term "midway" for a fair or carnival referred originally to the Midway Plaisance, a strip of park land that still runs through the University of Chicago campus and connects the Washington and Jackson Parks.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago's flourishing economy attracted huge numbers of new immigrants from Europe and migrants from the Eastern United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Of the total population in 1900, more than 77% were either foreign-born or born in the United States of foreign parentage.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Germans, Irish, Poles, Swedes, and Czechs made up nearly two-thirds of the foreign-born population (by 1900, whites were 98.1% of the city's population).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] During World War I and the 1920s there was a major expansion in industry.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The availability of jobs attracted African Americans from the Southern United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Between 1910 and 1930, the African American population of Chicago increased dramatically, from 44,103 to 233,903.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] This Great Migration had an immense cultural impact, called the Chicago Black Renaissance, part of the New Negro Movement, in art, literature, and music.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Continuing racial tensions and violence in the city, such as the Chicago race riot of 1919, also occurred.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The ratification of the 18th amendment to the Constitution in 1919 made the production and sale (including exportation) of alcoholic beverages illegal in the United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] This ushered in the beginning of what is known as the gangster era, a time that roughly spans from 1919 until 1933 when Prohibition was repealed.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The 1920s saw gangsters, including Al Capone, Dion O'Banion, Bugs Moran and Tony Accardo battle law enforcement and each other on the streets of Chicago during the Prohibition era.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago was the location of the infamous St.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Valentine's Day Massacre in 1929, when Al Capone sent men to gun down members of a rival gang, North Side, led by Bugs Moran, leaving seven rival members dead.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] From 1920 to 1921, the city was affected by a series of tenant rent strikes, which led to the formation of the Chicago Tenants Protective association, passage of the Kessenger tenant laws, and of a heat ordinance that legally required flats to be kept above 68 °F during winter months by landlords.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago was the first American city to have a homosexual-rights organization.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The organization, formed in 1924, was called the Society for Human Rights.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] It produced the first American publication for homosexuals, *Friendship and Freedom*.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Police and political pressure caused the organization to disband.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The Great Depression brought unprecedented suffering to Chicago, in no small part due to the city's heavy reliance on heavy industry.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Notably, industrial areas on the south side and neighborhoods lining both branches of the Chicago River were devastated; by 1933 over 50% of industrial jobs in the city had been lost, and unemployment rates amongst blacks and Latinos in the city were over 40%.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The Republican political machine in Chicago was utterly destroyed by the economic crisis, and every mayor since 1931 has been a Democrat.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] From 1928 to 1933, the city witnessed a tax revolt, and the city was unable to meet payroll or provide relief efforts.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The fiscal crisis was resolved by 1933, and at the same time, federal relief funding began to flow into Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago was also a hotbed of labor activism, with Unemployed Councils contributing heavily in the early depression to create solidarity for the poor and demand relief; these organizations were created by socialist and communist groups.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] By 1935, the Workers Alliance of America began organizing the poor, workers, the unemployed.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In the spring of 1937 Republic Steel Works witnessed the Memorial Day massacre of 1937 in the neighborhood of East Side.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 1933, Chicago Mayor Anton Cermak was fatally wounded in Miami, Florida, during a failed assassination attempt on President-elect Franklin D.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 1933 and 1934, the city celebrated its centennial by hosting the Century of Progress International Exposition World's Fair.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The theme of the fair was technological innovation over the century since Chicago's founding.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] During World War II, the city of Chicago alone produced more steel than the United Kingdom every year from 1939 – 1945, and more than Nazi Germany from 1943 – 1945.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The Great Migration, which had been on pause due to the Depression, resumed at an even faster pace in the second wave, as hundreds of thousands of blacks from the South arrived in the city to work in the steel mills, railroads, and shipping yards.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] On December 2, 1942, physicist Enrico Fermi conducted the world's first controlled nuclear reaction at the University of Chicago as part of the top-secret Manhattan Project.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] This led to the creation of the atomic bomb by the United States, which it used in World War II in 1945.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Daley, a Democrat, was elected in 1955, in the era of machine politics.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 1956, the city conducted its last major expansion when it annexed the land under O'Hare airport, including a small portion of DuPage County.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] By the 1960s, white residents in several neighborhoods left the city for the suburban areas – in many American cities, a process known as white flight – as Blacks continued to move beyond the Black Belt.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] While home loan discriminatory redlining against blacks continued, the real estate industry practiced what became known as blockbusting, completely changing the racial composition of whole neighborhoods.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Structural changes in industry, such as globalization and job outsourcing, caused heavy job losses for lower-skilled workers.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] At its peak during the 1960s, some 250,000 workers were employed in the steel industry in Chicago, but the steel crisis of the 1970s and 1980s reduced this number to just 28,000 in 2015.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 1966, Martin Luther King Jr. and Albert Raby led the Chicago Freedom Movement, which culminated in agreements between Mayor Richard J.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Two years later, the city hosted the tumultuous 1968 Democratic National Convention, which featured physical confrontations both inside and outside the convention hall, with anti-war protesters, journalists and bystanders being beaten by police.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Major construction projects, including the Sears Tower (now known as the Willis Tower, which in 1974 became the world's tallest building), University of Illinois at Chicago, McCormick Place, and O'Hare International Airport, were undertaken during Richard J.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 1979, Jane Byrne, the city's first female mayor, was elected.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] She was notable for temporarily moving into the crime-ridden Cabrini-Green housing project and leading Chicago's school system out of a financial crisis.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 1983, Harold Washington became the first black mayor of Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Washington's first term in office directed attention to poor and previously neglected minority neighborhoods.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] He was re‑elected in 1987 but died of a heart attack soon after.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Washington was succeeded by 6th ward alderperson Eugene Sawyer, who was elected by the Chicago City Council and served until a special election.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] His accomplishments included improvements to parks and creating incentives for sustainable development, as well as closing Meigs Field in the middle of the night and destroying the runways.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] After successfully running for re-election five times, and becoming Chicago's longest-serving mayor, Richard M.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Daley declined to run for a seventh term.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 1992, a construction accident near the Kinzie Street Bridge produced a breach connecting the Chicago River to a tunnel below, which was part of an abandoned freight tunnel system extending throughout the downtown Loop district.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The tunnels filled with 250 million US gallons (1,000,000 m3) of water, affecting buildings throughout the district and forcing a shutdown of electrical power.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The area was shut down for three days and some buildings did not reopen for weeks; losses were estimated at $1.95 billion.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] On February 23, 2011, Rahm Emanuel, a former White House Chief of Staff and member of the House of Representatives, won the mayoral election.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Emanuel was sworn in as mayor on May 16, 2011, and won re-election in 2015.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Lori Lightfoot, the city's first African American woman mayor and its first openly LGBTQ mayor, was elected to succeed Emanuel as mayor in 2019.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] All three city-wide elective offices were held by women (and women of color) for the first time in Chicago history: in addition to Lightfoot, the city clerk was Anna Valencia and the city treasurer was Melissa Conyears-Ervin.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] On May 15, 2023, Brandon Johnson assumed office as the 57th mayor of Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago is located in northeastern Illinois on the southwestern shores of freshwater Lake Michigan.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] It is the principal city in the Chicago Metropolitan Area, situated in both the Midwestern United States and the Great Lakes region.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The city rests on a continental divide at the site of the Chicago Portage, connecting the Mississippi River and the Great Lakes watersheds.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In addition to it lying beside Lake Michigan, two rivers—the Chicago River in downtown and the Calumet River in the industrial far South Side—flow either entirely or partially through the city.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago's history and economy are closely tied to its proximity to Lake Michigan.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] While the Chicago River historically handled much of the region's waterborne cargo, today's huge lake freighters use the city's Lake Calumet Harbor on the South Side.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The lake also provides another positive effect: moderating Chicago's climate, making waterfront neighborhoods slightly warmer in winter and cooler in summer.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] When Chicago was founded in 1837, most of the early building was around the mouth of the Chicago River, as can be seen on a map of the city's original 58 blocks.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The overall grade of the city's central, built-up areas is relatively consistent with the natural flatness of its overall natural geography, generally exhibiting only slight differentiation otherwise.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The average land elevation is 579 ft (176.5 m) above sea level.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] While measurements vary somewhat, the lowest points are along the lake shore at 578 ft (176.2 m), while the highest point, at 672 ft (205 m), is the morainal ridge of Blue Island in the city's far south side.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Lake Shore Drive runs adjacent to a large portion of Chicago's waterfront.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Some of the parks along the waterfront include Lincoln Park, Grant Park, Burnham Park, and Jackson Park.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] There are 24 public beaches across 26 miles (42 km) of the waterfront.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Landfill extends into portions of the lake providing space for Navy Pier, Northerly Island, the Museum Campus, and large portions of the McCormick Place Convention Center.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Most of the city's high-rise commercial and residential buildings are close to the waterfront.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] An informal name for the entire Chicago metropolitan area is "Chicagoland", which generally means the city and all its suburbs, though different organizations have slightly different definitions.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Major sections of the city include the central business district, called the Loop, and the North, South, and West Sides.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The three sides of the city are represented on the Flag of Chicago by three horizontal white stripes.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The North Side is the city's most densely populated residential section, and many high-rises are on this side of the city along the lakefront.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The South Side is the city's largest section, encompassing roughly 60% of its land area.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The South Side contains most of the facilities of the Port of Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In the late 1920s, sociologists at the University of Chicago subdivided the city into 75 distinct community areas, plus O'Hare in 1956 and Edgewater in 1980 for a total of 77.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The community areas can further be subdivided into over 200 informally defined neighborhoods.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago's streets were laid out in a street grid that grew from the city's original townsite plot, which was bounded by Lake Michigan on the east, North Avenue on the north, Wood Street on the west, and 22nd Street on the south.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Streets following the Public Land Survey System section lines later became arterial streets in outlying sections.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] As new additions to the city were platted, city ordinance required them to be laid out with eight streets to the mile in one direction and sixteen in the other direction, about one street per 200 meters in one direction and one street per 100 meters in the other direction.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The grid's regularity provided an efficient means of developing new real estate property.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] A scattering of diagonal streets, many of them originally Native American trails, also cross the city (Elston, Milwaukee, Ogden, Lincoln, etc.).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Many additional diagonal streets were recommended in the Plan of Chicago, but only the extension of Ogden Avenue was ever constructed.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 2021, Chicago was ranked the fourth-most walkable large city in the United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Many of the city's residential streets have a wide patch of grass or trees between the street and the sidewalk itself.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] This helps to keep pedestrians on the sidewalk further away from the street traffic.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago's Western Avenue is the longest continuous urban street in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Other notable streets include Michigan Avenue, State Street, 95th Street, Cicero Avenue, Clark Street, and Belmont Avenue.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The City Beautiful movement inspired Chicago's boulevards and parkways.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The destruction caused by the Great Chicago Fire led to the largest building boom in the history of the nation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 1885, the first steel-framed high-rise building, the Home Insurance Building, rose in the city as Chicago ushered in the skyscraper era, which would then be followed by many other cities around the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Today, Chicago's skyline is among the world's tallest and densest.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Some of the United States' tallest towers are located in Chicago; Willis Tower (formerly Sears Tower) is the third tallest building in the Western Hemisphere after One World Trade Center, and Central Park Tower.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The Loop's historic buildings include the Chicago Board of Trade Building, the Fine Arts Building, 35 East Wacker, and the Chicago Building, 860-880 Lake Shore Drive Apartments by Mies van der Rohe.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Many other architects have left their impression on the Chicago skyline such as Daniel Burnham, Louis Sullivan, Charles B.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The Merchandise Mart, once the largest building in the world, had its own zip code until 2008, and stands near the junction of the North and South branches of the Chicago River.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Presently, the four tallest buildings in the city are Willis Tower (formerly the Sears Tower, also a building with its own zip code), Trump International Hotel and Tower, the Aon Center (previously the Standard Oil Building), and the John Hancock Center.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Industrial districts, such as some areas on the South Side, the areas along the Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal, and the Northwest Indiana area are clustered.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago gave its name to the Chicago School and was home to the Prairie School, two movements in architecture.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Multiple kinds and scales of houses, townhouses, condominiums, and apartment buildings can be found throughout Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Large swaths of the city's residential areas away from the lake are characterized by brick bungalows built from the early 20th century through the end of World War II.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago is also a prominent center of the Polish Cathedral style of church architecture.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The Chicago suburb of Oak Park was home to famous architect Frank Lloyd Wright, who had designed The Robie House located near the University of Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] A popular tourist activity is to take an architecture boat tour along the Chicago River.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago is famous for its outdoor public art with donors establishing funding for such art as far back as Benjamin Ferguson's 1905 trust.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] A number of Chicago's public art works are by modern figurative artists.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Some events which shaped the city's history have also been memorialized by art works, including the Great Northern Migration (Saar) and the centennial of statehood for Illinois.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Finally, two fountains near the Loop also function as monumental works of art: Plensa's Crown Fountain as well as Burnham and Bennett's Buckingham Fountain.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The city mostly lies within the typical hot-summer humid continental climate (Köppen: *Dfa*), and experiences four distinct seasons.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Summers are hot and humid, with frequent heat waves.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The July daily average temperature is 75.4 °F (24.1 °C), with afternoon temperatures peaking at 84.5 °F (29.2 °C).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In a normal summer, temperatures reach at least 90 °F (32 °C) on 17 days, with lakefront locations staying cooler when winds blow off the lake.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Blizzards do occur, such as in winter 2011.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The normal winter high from December through March is about 36 °F (2 °C).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] January and February are the coldest months.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] A polar vortex in January 2019 nearly broke the city's cold record of −27 °F (−33 °C), which was set on January 20, 1985.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Measurable snowfall can continue through the first or second week of April.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Spring and autumn are mild, short seasons, typically with low humidity.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Dew point temperatures in the summer range from an average of 55.8 °F (13.2 °C) in June to 61.7 °F (16.5 °C) in July.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] They can reach nearly 80 °F (27 °C), such as during the July 2019 heat wave.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The city lies within USDA plant hardiness zone 6a, transitioning to 5b in the suburbs.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] According to the National Weather Service, Chicago's highest official temperature reading of 105 °F (41 °C) was recorded on July 24, 1934.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Midway Airport reached 109 °F (43 °C) one day prior and recorded a heat index of 125 °F (52 °C) during the 1995 heatwave.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The lowest official temperature of −27 °F (−33 °C) was recorded on January 20, 1985, at O'Hare Airport.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Most of the city's rainfall is brought by thunderstorms, averaging 38 a year.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The region is prone to severe thunderstorms during the spring and summer which can produce large hail, damaging winds, and occasionally tornadoes.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Notably, the F4 Oak Lawn tornado moved through the South Side of the city on April 21, 1967, moving onto Lake Michigan as a waterspout.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Downtown Chicago was struck by an F3 tornado on May 6, 1876, again moving out over Lake Michigan.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Like other major cities, Chicago experiences an urban heat island, making the city and its suburbs milder than surrounding rural areas, especially at night and in winter.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Northeast winds from wintertime cyclones departing south of the region sometimes bring the city lake-effect snow.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] During its first hundred years, Chicago was one of the fastest-growing cities in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] When founded in 1833, fewer than 200 people had settled on what was then the American frontier.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] By the time of its first census, seven years later, the population had reached over 4,000.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In the forty years from 1850 to 1890, the city's population grew from slightly under 30,000 to over 1 million.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] By the 1890 census, Chicago was the second most populous city in the United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] By 1900, it was the fifth largest in the world behind Berlin, Paris, New York, and London, and the largest city founded in the prior century.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Within sixty years of the Great Chicago Fire of 1871, the population went from about 300,000 to over 3 million, and reached its highest ever recorded population of 3.6 million for the 1950 census.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] To these ethnic groups, the basis of the city's industrial working class, were added an additional influx of African Americans from the American South as part of the Great Migration—with Chicago's black population doubling between 1910 and 1920 and doubling again between 1920 and 1930.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago has a significant Bosnian population, many of whom arrived in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In the 1920s and 1930s, the great majority of African Americans moving to Chicago settled in a so‑called "Black Belt" on the city's South Side.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] A large number of blacks also settled on the West Side.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] By 1930, two-thirds of Chicago's black population lived in sections of the city which were 90% black in racial composition.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Around that time, the block of 4600 Winthrop Avenue in the Uptown neighborhood was the only one in the neighborhood on which African Americans could live or open establishments.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago's South Side emerged as United States second-largest urban black concentration, following New York's Harlem.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 1990, Chicago's South Side and the adjoining south suburbs constituted the largest black majority region in the entire United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Since the 1980s, Chicago has had a massive exodus of African Americans (primarily from the South and West sides) to its suburbs or outside its metropolitan area.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The above average crime and cost of living were leading reasons for the fast declining African American population in Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Most of Chicago's foreign-born population were born in Mexico, Poland or India.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] A 2020 study estimated the total Jewish population of the Chicago metropolitan area, both religious and irreligious, at 319,500.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago's population declined in the latter half of the 20th century, from over 3.6 million in 1950 down to under 2.7 million by 2010.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] By the time of the official census count in 1990, it was overtaken by Los Angeles as the United States' second largest city.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] It then saw a rise in population for the 2000 census, a decrease in 2010, and another increase for the 2020 census.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] According to U.S. census estimates as of July 2019, Chicago's largest racial or ethnic group is non-Hispanic White at 32.8% of the population, Blacks at 30.1% and the Hispanic population at 29.0% of the population.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago became a "de jure" sanctuary city in 2012 when Mayor Rahm Emanuel and the City Council passed the Welcoming City Ordinance.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Census Bureau's American Community Survey data estimates for 2022, the median income for a household in the city was $70,386, and the per capita income was $45,449.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Male full-time workers had a median income of $68,870 versus $60,987 for females.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] About 17.2% of the population lived below the poverty line.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 2018, Chicago ranked seventh globally for the highest number of ultra-high-net-worth residents with roughly 3,300 residents worth more than $30 million.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Persons who did not report or classify an ancestry were 548,790.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago has the third-largest lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, and queer (LGBTQ) population in the United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Since the 2013 legalization of same-sex marriage in Illinois, over 10,000 same-sex couples have wed in Illinois' Cook County, a majority of them in Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago is the first U.S. city to have a pro-gay organization and consistently ranks as one of the most LGBTQ-friendly cities in the nation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Lake View and Edgewater are historically the epicenters of LGBTQ culture in Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] According to a 2014 study by the Pew Research Center, Christianity is the most prevalently practiced religion in Chicago (71%), with the city being the fourth-most religious metropolis in the United States after Dallas, Atlanta and Houston.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Roman Catholicism and Protestantism are the largest branches (34% and 35% respectively), followed by Eastern Orthodoxy and Jehovah's Witnesses with 1% each.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago also has a sizable non-Christian population.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Non-Christian groups include Irreligious (22%), Judaism (3%), Islam (2%), Buddhism (1%) and Hinduism (1%).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Chicago is the headquarters of several religious denominations, including the Evangelical Covenant Church and the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The Fourth Presbyterian Church is one of the largest Presbyterian congregations in the United States based on memberships.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Since the 20th century Chicago has also been the headquarters of the Assyrian Church of the East.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] In 2014 the Catholic Church was the largest individual Christian denomination (34%), with the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Chicago being the largest Catholic jurisdiction.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Evangelical Protestantism form the largest theological Protestant branch (16%), followed by Mainline Protestants (11%), and historically Black churches (8%).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Among denominational Protestant branches, Baptists formed the largest group in Chicago (10%); followed by Nondenominational (5%); Lutherans (4%); and Pentecostals (3%).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Non-Christian faiths accounted for 7% of the religious population in 2014.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Judaism has at least 261,000 adherents which is 3% of the population.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] The first two Parliament of the World's Religions in 1893 and 1993 were held in Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Many international religious leaders have visited Chicago, including Mother Teresa, the Dalai Lama and Pope John Paul II in 1979.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p01] Pope Leo XIV was born in Chicago in 1955 and graduated from the Catholic Theological Union in Hyde Park.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago has the third-largest gross metropolitan product in the United States—about $670.5 billion according to September 2017 estimates.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city has also been rated as having the most balanced economy in the United States, due to its high level of diversification.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago metropolitan area has the third-largest science and engineering work force of any metropolitan area in the nation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago was the base of commercial operations for industrialists John Crerar, John Whitfield Bunn, Richard Teller Crane, Marshall Field, John Farwell, Julius Rosenwald, and many other commercial visionaries who laid the foundation for Midwestern and global industry.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago is a major world financial center, with the second-largest central business district in the United States, following Midtown Manhattan.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city is the seat of the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago, the Bank's Seventh District.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city has major financial and futures exchanges, including the Chicago Stock Exchange, the Cboe Global Markets Options Exchange, and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange (the "Merc"), which is owned, along with the Chicago Board of Trade (CBOT), by Chicago's CME Group.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] In 2017, Chicago exchanges traded 4.7 billion in derivatives.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chase Bank has its commercial and retail banking headquarters in Chicago's Chase Tower.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Academically, Chicago has been influential through the Chicago school of economics, which fielded 12 Nobel Prize winners.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city and its surrounding metropolitan area contain the third-largest labor pool in the United States with about 4.63 million workers.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Illinois is home to 66 *Fortune* 1000 companies, including those in Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city of Chicago also hosts 12 *Fortune* Global 500 companies and 17 *Financial Times* 500 companies.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city claims three Dow 30 companies: aerospace giant Boeing, which moved its headquarters from Seattle to the Chicago Loop in 2001; McDonald's; and Walgreens Boots Alliance.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] For six consecutive years from 2013 through 2018, Chicago was ranked the nation's top metropolitan area for corporate relocations.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] However, three *Fortune* 500 companies left Chicago in 2022, leaving the city with 35, still second to New York City.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Manufacturing, printing, publishing, and food processing also play major roles in the city's economy.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Several medical products and services companies are based in the Chicago area, including Baxter International, Boeing, Abbott Laboratories, and the Healthcare division of General Electric.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Prominent food companies based in Chicago include the world headquarters of Conagra, Ferrara Candy Company, Kraft Heinz, McDonald's, Mondelez International, and Quaker Oats.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago has been a hub of the retail sector since its early development, with Montgomery Ward, Sears, and Marshall Field's.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Today the Chicago metropolitan area is the headquarters of several retailers, including Walgreens, Sears, Ace Hardware, Claire's, ULTA Beauty, and Crate & Barrel.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Tech companies based in the area include CDW, Uber Frieght, Zebra Technologies, Motorola Solutions, Motorola along with regional offices for Google, Salesforce, LinkedIn, and more.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago was also the site of the Schwinn Bicycle Company.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago is a major world convention destination.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city's main convention center is McCormick Place.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] With its four interconnected buildings, it is the largest convention center in the nation and third-largest in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] (behind Las Vegas and Orlando) in number of conventions hosted annually.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago's minimum wage for non-tipped employees is one of the highest in the nation and reached $15 in 2021.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city's waterfront location and nightlife attracts residents and tourists alike.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Over a third of the city population is concentrated in the lakefront neighborhoods from Rogers Park in the north to South Shore in the south.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city has many upscale dining establishments as well as many ethnic restaurant districts.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Downtown is the center of Chicago's financial, cultural, governmental, and commercial institutions and the site of Grant Park and many of the city's skyscrapers.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Many of the city's financial institutions, such as the CBOT and the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago, are located within a section of downtown called "The Loop", which is an eight-block by five-block area of city streets that is encircled by elevated rail tracks.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The term "The Loop" is largely used by locals to refer to the entire downtown area as well.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The central area includes the Near North Side, the Near South Side, and the Near West Side, as well as the Loop.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] These areas contribute famous skyscrapers, abundant restaurants, shopping, museums, Soldier Field, convention facilities, parkland, and beaches.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Lincoln Park contains Lincoln Park Zoo and Lincoln Park Conservatory.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The River North Gallery District features the nation's largest concentration of contemporary art galleries outside of New York City.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Lake View is home to Boystown, the city's large LGBT nightlife and culture center.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago Pride Parade, held the last Sunday in June, is one of the world's largest with over a million people in attendance.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] North Halsted Street is the main thoroughfare of Boystown.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The South Side neighborhood of Hyde Park is the home of former U.S.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] President Barack Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The neighborhood is home to the Barack Obama Presidential Center, a museum and library dedicated to his presidency.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] It also contains the University of Chicago, ranked one of the world's top ten universities, and the Museum of Science and Industry.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The 6-mile (9.7 km) long Burnham Park stretches along the waterfront of the South Side.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Two of the city's largest parks are also located on this side of the city: Jackson Park, bordering the waterfront, hosted the World's Columbian Exposition in 1893, and is the site of the aforementioned museum; and slightly west sits Washington Park.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The two parks themselves are connected by a wide strip of parkland called the Midway Plaisance, running adjacent to the University of Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The South Side hosts one of the city's largest parades, the annual African American Bud Billiken Parade and Picnic, which travels through Bronzeville to Washington Park.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Ford Motor Company has an automobile assembly plant on the South Side in Hegewisch, and most of the facilities of the Port of Chicago are also on the South Side.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The West Side holds the Garfield Park Conservatory, one of the largest collections of tropical plants in any U.S. city.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Prominent Latino cultural attractions found here include Humboldt Park's Institute of Puerto Rican Arts and Culture and the annual Puerto Rican People's Parade, as well as the National Museum of Mexican Art and St.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Near West Side holds the University of Illinois at Chicago and was once home to Oprah Winfrey's Harpo Studios, the site of which has been rebuilt as the global headquarters of McDonald's.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city's distinctive accent, made famous by its use in classic films like *The Blues Brothers* and television programs like the *Saturday Night Live* skit "Bill Swerski's Superfans", is an advanced form of Inland Northern American English.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] This dialect can be found in other cities bordering the Great Lakes, such as Detroit, Cleveland, Milwaukee, and Buffalo, New York, and most prominently features a rearrangement of certain vowel sounds, such as the short "a" sound as in "cat", which can sound more like "kyet" to outsiders.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The accent remains well associated with the city.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Renowned Chicago theater companies include the Goodman Theatre in the Loop; the Steppenwolf Theatre Company and Victory Gardens Theater in Lincoln Park; and the Chicago Shakespeare Theater at Navy Pier.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Broadway In Chicago offers Broadway-style entertainment at five theaters: the Nederlander Theatre, CIBC Theatre, Cadillac Palace Theatre, Auditorium Building of Roosevelt University, and Broadway Playhouse at Water Tower Place.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Polish language productions for Chicago's large Polish speaking population can be seen at the historic Gateway Theatre in Jefferson Park.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Since 1968, the Joseph Jefferson Awards are given annually to acknowledge excellence in theater in the Chicago area.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago's theater community spawned modern improvisational theater, and includes the prominent groups The Second City and I.O.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago Symphony Orchestra (CSO) performs at Symphony Center, and is recognized as one of the best orchestras in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Also performing regularly at Symphony Center is the Chicago Sinfonietta, a more diverse and multicultural counterpart to the CSO.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] In the summer, many outdoor concerts are given in Grant Park and Millennium Park.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Ravinia Festival, located 25 miles (40 km) north of Chicago, is the summer home of the CSO, and is a favorite destination for many Chicagoans.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Civic Opera House is home to the Lyric Opera of Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Lithuanian Opera Company of Chicago was founded by Lithuanian Chicagoans in 1956, and presents operas in Lithuanian.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Joffrey Ballet and Chicago Festival Ballet perform in various venues, including the Harris Theater in Millennium Park.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago has several other contemporary and jazz dance troupes, such as the Hubbard Street Dance Chicago and Chicago Dance Crash.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Other live-music genre which are part of the city's cultural heritage include Chicago blues, Chicago soul, jazz, and gospel.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city is the birthplace of house music (a popular form of electronic dance music) and industrial music, and is the site of an influential hip hop scene.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] In the 1980s and 90s, the city was the global center for house and industrial music, two forms of music created in Chicago, as well as being popular for alternative rock, punk, and new wave.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city has been a center for rave culture, since the 1980s.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] A flourishing independent rock music culture brought forth Chicago indie.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Annual festivals feature various acts, such as Lollapalooza and the Pitchfork Music Festival.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Lollapalooza originated in 1991 as a touring festival, but as of 2005 its home has been Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] A 2007 report on the Chicago music industry by the University of Chicago Cultural Policy Center ranked Chicago third among metropolitan U.S. areas in "size of music industry" and fourth among all U.S. cities in "number of concerts and performances".
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago has a distinctive fine art tradition.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] For much of the twentieth century, it nurtured a strong style of figurative surrealism, as in the works of Ivan Albright and Ed Paschke.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] In 1968 and 1969, members of the Chicago Imagists, such as Roger Brown, Leon Golub, Robert Lostutter, Jim Nutt, and Barbara Rossi produced bizarre representational paintings.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Henry Darger is one of the most celebrated figures of outsider art.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] In 2014, Chicago attracted 50.17 million domestic leisure travelers, 11.09 million domestic business travelers and 1.308 million overseas visitors.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] These visitors contributed more than US$13.7 billion to Chicago's economy.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Upscale shopping along the Magnificent Mile and State Street, thousands of restaurants, as well as Chicago's architecture, continue to draw tourists.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city is the United States' third-largest convention destination.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] A 2017 study by Walk Score ranked Chicago the sixth-most walkable of fifty largest cities in the United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Most conventions are held at McCormick Place, just south of Soldier Field.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Navy Pier, located just east of Streeterville, is 3,000 ft (910 m) long and houses retail stores, restaurants, museums, exhibition halls and auditoriums.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Ferris wheel first appeared at the World's Columbian Exposition, held in Chicago in 1893.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Willis Tower, formerly named Sears Tower, is a popular destination for tourists.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Among the city's museums are the Adler Planetarium & Astronomy Museum, the Field Museum of Natural History, and the Shedd Aquarium.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Museum Campus joins the southern section of Grant Park, which includes the renowned Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Buckingham Fountain anchors the downtown park along the lakefront.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The University of Chicago's Institute for the Study of Ancient Cultures, West Asia & North Africa has an extensive collection of ancient Egyptian and Near Eastern archaeological artifacts.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago lays claim to a large number of regional specialties that reflect the city's ethnic and working-class roots.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Included among these are its nationally renowned deep-dish pizza; this style is said to have originated at Pizzeria Uno.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago-style thin crust is also popular in the city.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Certain Chicago pizza favorites include Lou Malnati's and Giordano's.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago-style hot dog, typically an all-beef hot dog, is loaded with an array of toppings that often includes pickle relish, yellow mustard, pickled sport peppers, tomato wedges, dill pickle spear and topped off with celery salt on a poppy seed bun.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Enthusiasts of the Chicago-style hot dog frown upon the use of ketchup as a garnish, but may prefer to add giardiniera.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] A distinctly Chicago sandwich, the Italian beef sandwich is thinly sliced beef simmered in au jus and served on an Italian roll with sweet peppers or spicy giardiniera.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] A popular modification is the Combo—an Italian beef sandwich with the addition of an Italian sausage.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Maxwell Street Polish is a grilled or deep-fried kielbasa—on a hot dog roll, topped with grilled onions, yellow mustard, and hot sport peppers.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicken Vesuvio is roasted bone-in chicken cooked in oil and garlic next to garlicky oven-roasted potato wedges and a sprinkling of green peas.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Puerto Rican-influenced jibarito is a sandwich made with flattened, fried green plantains instead of bread.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The mother-in-law is a tamale topped with chili and served on a hot dog bun.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The tradition of serving the Greek dish saganaki while aflame has its origins in Chicago's Greek community.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The appetizer, which consists of a square of fried cheese, is doused with Metaxa and flambéed table-side.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago-style barbecue features hardwood smoked rib tips and hot links which were traditionally cooked in an aquarium smoker, a Chicago invention.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Annual festivals feature various Chicago signature dishes, such as Taste of Chicago and the Chicago Food Truck Festival.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] One of the world's most decorated restaurants and a recipient of three Michelin stars, Alinea is located in Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Well-known chefs who have had restaurants in Chicago include: Charlie Trotter, Rick Tramonto, Grant Achatz, and Rick Bayless.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] In 2003, *Robb Report* named Chicago the country's "most exceptional dining destination".
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago literature finds its roots in the city's tradition of lucid, direct journalism, lending to a strong tradition of social realism.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Narrative fiction of that time, much of it in the style of "high-flown romance" and "genteel realism", needed a new approach to describe the urban social, political, and economic conditions of Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Nonetheless, Chicagoans worked hard to create a literary tradition that would stand the test of time, and create a "city of feeling" out of concrete, steel, vast lake, and open prairie.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Much notable Chicago fiction focuses on the city itself, with social criticism keeping exultation in check.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] At least three short periods in the history of Chicago have had a lasting influence on American literature.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] These include from the time of the Great Chicago Fire to about 1900, what became known as the Chicago Literary Renaissance in the 1910s and early 1920s, and the period of the Great Depression to the 1940s.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] What would become the influential *Poetry* magazine was founded in 1912 by Harriet Monroe, who was working as an art critic for the *Chicago Tribune*.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The magazine discovered such poets as Gwendolyn Brooks, James Merrill, and John Ashbery.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Eliot's first professionally published poem, "The Love Song of J.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Alfred Prufrock", was first published by *Poetry*.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Contributors have included Ezra Pound, William Butler Yeats, William Carlos Williams, Langston Hughes, and Carl Sandburg, among others.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The magazine was instrumental in launching the Imagist and Objectivist poetic movements.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] From the 1950s to the 1970s, American poetry continued to evolve in Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] In the 1980s, a modern form of poetry performance began in Chicago, the poetry slam.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city has two Major League Baseball (MLB) teams: the Chicago Cubs of the National League play in Wrigley Field on the North Side; and the Chicago White Sox of the American League play in Rate Field on the South Side.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The two teams have faced each other in a World Series only once, in 1906.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Cubs are the oldest Major League Baseball team to have never changed their city; they have played in Chicago since 1871.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] They had the dubious honor of having the longest championship drought in American professional sports, failing to win a World Series between 1908 and 2016.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The White Sox have played on the South Side continuously since 1901.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] They have won three World Series titles (1906, 1917, 2005) and six American League pennants, including the first in 1901.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago Bears, one of the last two remaining charter members of the National Football League (NFL), have won nine NFL Championships, including the 1985 Super Bowl XX.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Bears play their home games at Soldier Field.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago Bulls of the National Basketball Association (NBA) is one of the most recognized basketball teams in the world.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] During the 1990s, with Michael Jordan leading them, the Bulls won six NBA championships in eight seasons.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago Blackhawks of the National Hockey League (NHL) began play in 1926, and are one of the "Original Six" teams of the NHL.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Blackhawks have won six Stanley Cups, including in 2010, 2013, and 2015.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Both the Bulls and the Blackhawks play at the United Center.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago Fire FC is a member of Major League Soccer (MLS) and plays at Soldier Field.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Fire have won one league title and four U.S.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Open Cups, since their founding in 1997.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] In 1994, the United States hosted a successful FIFA World Cup with games played at Soldier Field.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago Stars FC are a team in the National Women's Soccer League (NWSL).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] They previously played in Women's Professional Soccer (WPS), of which they were a founding member, before joining the NWSL in 2013.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] They play at SeatGeek Stadium in Bridgeview, Illinois.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago Sky is a professional basketball team playing in the Women's National Basketball Association (WNBA).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] They play home games at the Wintrust Arena.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The team was founded before the 2006 WNBA season began.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago Marathon has been held each year since 1977 except for 1987, when a half marathon was run in its place.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago Marathon is one of six World Marathon Majors.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago Street Course in downtown Chicago had races in the Cup Series and Xfinity Series from 2023 to 2025, while the often forgotten Chicago Motor Speedway held CART and NASCAR Truck Series races.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago has also entered into esports with the creation of the OpTic Chicago, a professional Call of Duty team that participates within the CDL.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] When Chicago was incorporated in 1837, it chose the motto *Urbs in Horto*, a Latin phrase which means "City in a Garden".
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Today, the Chicago Park District consists of more than 570 parks with over 8,000 acres (3,200 ha) of municipal parkland.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] There are 31 sand beaches, a plethora of museums, two world-class conservatories, and 50 nature areas.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Lincoln Park, the largest of the city's parks, covers 1,200 acres (490 ha) and has over 20 million visitors each year, making it third in the number of visitors after Central Park in New York City, and the National Mall and Memorial Parks in Washington, D.C.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] There is a historic boulevard system, a network of wide, tree-lined boulevards which connect a number of Chicago parks.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The boulevards and the parks were authorized by the Illinois legislature in 1869.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] A number of Chicago neighborhoods emerged along these roadways in the 19th century.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The building of the boulevard system continued intermittently until 1942.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] It includes nineteen boulevards, eight parks, and six squares, along twenty-six miles of interconnected streets.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The *Chicago Park Boulevard System Historic District* was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2018.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] With berths for more than 6,000 boats, the Chicago Park District operates the nation's largest municipal harbor system.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Washington Park is also one of the city's biggest parks; covering nearly 400 acres (160 ha).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The park is listed on the National Register of Historic Places listings in South Side Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The government of the City of Chicago is divided into executive and legislative branches.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The mayor of Chicago is the chief executive, elected by general election for a term of four years, with no term limits.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The mayor appoints commissioners and other officials who oversee the various departments.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] As well as the mayor, Chicago's clerk and treasurer are also elected citywide.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The City Council is the legislative branch and is made up of 50 alderpersons, one elected from each ward in the city.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The council takes official action through the passage of ordinances and resolutions and approves the city budget.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago Police Department provides law enforcement and the Chicago Fire Department provides fire suppression and emergency medical services for the city and its residents.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Civil and criminal law cases are heard in the Cook County Circuit Court of the State of Illinois court system, or in the Northern District of Illinois, in the federal system.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] In the state court, the public prosecutor is the Illinois state's attorney; in the Federal court it is the United States attorney.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] During much of the last half of the 19th century, Chicago's politics were dominated by a growing Democratic Party organization.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] During the 1880s and 1890s, Chicago had a powerful radical tradition with large and highly organized socialist, anarchist and labor organizations.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] For much of the 20th century, Chicago has been among the largest and most reliable Democratic strongholds in the United States; with Chicago's Democratic vote the state of Illinois has been "solid blue" in presidential elections since 1992.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Even before then, it was not unheard of for Republican presidential candidates to win handily in downstate Illinois, only to lose statewide due to large Democratic margins in Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The citizens of Chicago have not elected a Republican mayor since 1927, when William Thompson was voted into office.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The strength of the party in Chicago is partly a consequence of Illinois state politics, where the Republicans have come to represent rural and farm concerns while the Democrats support urban issues such as Chicago's public school funding.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago contains less than 25% of the state's population, but it is split between eight of Illinois' 17 districts in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] All eight of the city's representatives are Democrats; only two Republicans have represented a significant portion of the city since 1973, for one term each: Robert P.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Hanrahan from 1973 to 1975, and Michael Patrick Flanagan from 1995 to 1997.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Machine politics persisted in Chicago after the decline of similar machines in other large U.S. cities.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] During much of that time, the city administration found opposition mainly from a liberal "independent" faction of the Democratic Party.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The independents finally gained control of city government in 1983 with the election of Harold Washington (in office 1983–1987).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] From 1989 until May 16, 2011, Chicago was under the leadership of its longest-serving mayor, Richard M.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Because of the dominance of the Democratic Party in Chicago, the Democratic primary vote held in the spring is generally more significant than the general elections in November for U.S.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The aldermanic, mayoral, and other city offices are filled through nonpartisan elections with runoffs as needed.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city is home of former United States President Barack Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama; Barack Obama was formerly a state legislator representing Chicago and later a U.S. senator.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Obamas' residence is located near the University of Chicago in Kenwood on the city's south side.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago experienced major rises in violent crime in the 1920s, in the late 1960s, and in the 2020s.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago's biggest criminal justice challenges have changed little over the last 50 years, and statistically reside with homicide, armed robbery, gang violence, and aggravated battery.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago has a higher murder rate than the larger cities of New York and Los Angeles.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] However, while it has a large absolute number of crimes due to its size, Chicago is not among the top-25 most violent cities in the United States.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Murder rates in Chicago vary greatly depending on the neighborhood in question.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The neighborhoods of Englewood on the South Side, and Austin on the West side, for example, have homicide rates that are ten times higher than other parts of the city.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago has an estimated population of over 100,000 active gang members from nearly 60 factions.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] According to reports in 2013, "most of Chicago's violent crime comes from gangs trying to maintain control of drug-selling territories," and is specifically related to the activities of the Sinaloa Cartel, which is active in several American cities.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Violent crime rates vary significantly by area of the city, with more economically developed areas having low rates, but other sections have much higher rates of crime.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] In 2013, the violent crime rate was 910 per 100,000 people; the murder rate was 10.4 per 100,000 – while high crime districts saw 38.9 murders, low crime districts saw 2.5 murders per 100,000.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago's long history of public corruption regularly draws the attention of federal law enforcement and federal prosecutors.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] From 2012 to 2019, 33 Chicago alderpersons were convicted on corruption charges, roughly one third of those elected in the time period.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] A report from the Office of the Legislative Inspector General noted that over half of Chicago's elected alderpersons took illegal campaign contributions in 2013.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Most corruption cases in Chicago are prosecuted by the U.S.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Attorney's office, as legal jurisdiction makes most offenses punishable as a federal crime.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago Public Schools (CPS) is the governing body of the school district that contains over 600 public elementary and high schools citywide, including several selective-admission magnet schools.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] There are eleven selective enrollment high schools in the Chicago Public Schools, designed to meet the needs of Chicago's most academically advanced students.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] These schools offer a rigorous curriculum with mainly honors and Advanced Placement (AP) courses.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Walter Payton College Prep High School is ranked number one in the city of Chicago and the state of Illinois.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago high school rankings are determined by the average test scores on state achievement tests.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The district, with an enrollment exceeding 400,545 students (2013–2014 20th Day Enrollment), is the third-largest in the U.S.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] In September 2012, teachers for the Chicago Teachers Union went on strike for the first time since 1987 over pay, resources, and other issues.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] According to 2014 data, Chicago's "choice system", where students who test or apply and may attend one of approximately 130 public high schools, sorts students of different achievement levels into different schools (high performing, middle performing, and low performing schools).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago has a network of Lutheran schools, and several private schools are run by other denominations and faiths, such as the Ida Crown Jewish Academy in West Ridge.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Chicago operates Catholic schools, including Jesuit preparatory schools and others.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] A number of private schools are completely secular.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] There is also the private Chicago Academy for the Arts, a high school focused on six different artistic disciplines, and the public Chicago High School for the Arts, a high school focused on five disciplines (visual arts, theatre, musical theatre, dance, and music).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago Public Library system operates three regional libraries and 77 neighborhood branches, including the central library.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Since the 1850s, Chicago has been a world center of higher education and research with several universities.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] These institutions consistently rank among the top "National Universities" in the United States, as determined by *U.S.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Highly regarded universities in Chicago and the surrounding area are the University of Chicago; Northwestern University; Illinois Institute of Technology; Loyola University Chicago; DePaul University; Columbia College Chicago and the University of Illinois Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] William Rainey Harper, the first president of the University of Chicago, was instrumental in the creation of the junior college concept, establishing nearby Joliet Junior College as the first in the nation in 1901.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] His legacy continues with the multiple community colleges in the Chicago proper, including the seven City Colleges of Chicago: Richard J.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Daley College, Kennedy–King College, Malcolm X College, Olive–Harvey College, Truman College, Harold Washington College, and Wilbur Wright College, in addition to the privately held MacCormac College.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The Chicago metropolitan area is a major media hub and the third-largest media market in the United States, after New York City and Los Angeles.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Each of the big five U.S. television networks, NBC, ABC, CBS, Fox and The CW, directly owns and operates a high-definition television station in Chicago (WMAQ 5, WLS 7, WBBM 2, WFLD 32 and WGN-TV 9, respectively).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] WGN is owned by the CW through a majority stake held in the network by the Nexstar Media Group, which acquired it from its founding owner Tribune Broadcasting in 2019.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] WGN was once carried, with some programming differences, as "WGN America" on cable and satellite TV nationwide and in parts of the Caribbean.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] WGN America eventually became NewsNation in 2021.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago has been the home of several prominent talk shows, including *The Oprah Winfrey Show*, *Steve Harvey Show*, *The Rosie Show*, *The Jerry Springer Show*, *The Phil Donahue Show*, *The Jenny Jones Show*, and more.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The city has one PBS member station (its second: WYCC 20, removed its affiliation with PBS in 2017): WTTW 11, producer of shows such as *Sneak Previews*, *The Frugal Gourmet*, *Lamb Chop's Play-Along* and *The McLaughlin Group*.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] As of 2018, *Windy City Live* is Chicago's only daytime talk show, which is hosted by Val Warner and Ryan Chiaverini at ABC7 Studios with a live weekday audience.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Since 1999, *Judge Mathis* also films his syndicated arbitration-based reality court show at the NBC Tower.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Beginning in January 2019, *Newsy* began producing 12 of its 14 hours of live news programming per day from its new facility in Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Most of Chicago's television stations are owned and operated by the big television network companies.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Two major daily newspapers are published in Chicago: the *Chicago Tribune* and the *Chicago Sun-Times*, with the Tribune having the larger circulation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] The entertainment and cultural magazine *Time Out Chicago* and *GRAB* magazine are published in the city, as well as local music magazine *Chicago Innerview*.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago is the home of satirical national news outlet, *The Onion*, and its sister pop-culture publication, *The A.V.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago has five 50,000 watt AM radio stations: the Audacy-owned WBBM and WSCR; the Tribune Broadcasting-owned WGN; the Cumulus Media-owned WLS; and the ESPN Radio-owned WMVP.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] Chicago is also home to a number of national radio shows, including *Beyond the Beltway* with Bruce DuMont on Sunday evenings.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p02] WBEZ produces nationally aired programs such as PRI's *This American Life* and NPR's *Wait Wait...Don't Tell Me!*.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Chicago is a major transportation hub in the United States and North America.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] It is an important component in global distribution, as it is the third-largest inter-modal port in the world after Hong Kong and Singapore.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The city of Chicago has a higher than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] In 2015, 26.5 percent of Chicago households were without a car, and increased slightly to 27.5 percent in 2016.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Chicago averaged 1.12 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Due to Chicago's wheel tax, residents of Chicago who own a vehicle are required to purchase a Chicago City Vehicle Sticker.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] In established Residential Parking Zones, only local residents can purchase Zone-specific parking stickers for themselves and guests.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Chicago since 2009 has relinquished rights to its public street parking.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] In 2008, as Chicago struggled to close a growing budget deficit, the city agreed to a 75-year, $1.16 billion deal to lease its parking meter system to an operating company created by Morgan Stanley, called Chicago Parking Meters LLC.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The rights of the parking ticket lease end in 2081, and since 2022 have already recouped over $1.5 billion in revenue for Chicago Parking Meters LLC investors.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Eight mainline and four auxiliary interstate highways (41 (mostly in Wisconsin), 55, 57, 65 (only in Indiana), 80 (also in Indiana), 88, 90 (also in Indiana), 94 (also in Indiana), 190, 290, 294, and 355) run through Chicago and its suburbs.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] I-490 is currently under construction on the west side of O'Hare Airport.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Segments that link to the city center are named after influential politicians, with three of them named after former U.S.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Presidents (Eisenhower, Kennedy, and Reagan) and one named after two-time Democratic candidate Adlai Stevenson.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The Kennedy and Dan Ryan Expressways are the busiest state maintained routes in the entire state of Illinois.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The Regional Transportation Authority (RTA) coordinates the operation of the three service boards: CTA, Metra, and Pace.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Beginning in June 2026, the RTA will be replaced by the Northern Illinois Transit Authority (NITA).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The Northern Indiana Commuter Transportation District (NICTD) operates the South Shore Line, which provides commuter rail service from Millennium Station to Northwest Indiana.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Since March 2026, it consists of two services: the Lakeshore Corridor to South Bend and the Monon Corridor to Munster/Dyer.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Greyhound Lines provides inter-city bus service to and from the city at the Chicago Bus Station, and Chicago is also the hub for the Midwest network of Megabus.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Amtrak long distance and inter-city rail services originate from Chicago Union Station.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Chicago is one of the largest hubs of passenger rail service in the nation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The services terminate in Port Huron, St.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Paul, the San Francisco Area, New York City, New Orleans, Portland, Oregon, Seattle, Miami, Milwaukee, Carbondale, Quincy, Boston, St.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Louis, Kansas City, Grand Rapids, Los Angeles, San Antonio, and Pontiac, Michigan.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Future service will terminate at Moline.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Chicago has a total of four active rail terminals: Chicago Union Station, Ogilvie Transportation Center, LaSalle Street Station, and Millennium Station.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Amtrak only serves Union Station, while Metra serves all four stations.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The South Shore Line services uses Millennium Station as its Chicago terminal.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] In July 2013, the bicycle-sharing system Divvy was launched with 750 bikes and 75 docking stations.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] It is operated by Lyft for the Chicago Department of Transportation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] As of July 2019, Divvy operated 5800 bicycles at 608 stations, covering almost all of the city, excluding Pullman, Rosedale, Beverly, Belmont Cragin and Edison Park.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] In May 2019, The City of Chicago announced its Chicago's Electric Shared Scooter Pilot Program, scheduled to run from June 15 to October 15.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The program started on June 15 with 10 different scooter companies, including scooter sharing market leaders Bird, Jump, Lime and Lyft.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Each company was allowed to bring 250 electric scooters, although both Bird and Lime claimed that they experienced a higher demand for their scooters.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The program ended on October 15, with nearly 800,000 rides taken.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Chicago is the largest hub in the railroad industry.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] All five Class I railroads meet in Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] As of 2002, severe freight train congestion caused trains to take as long to get through the Chicago region as it took to get there from the West Coast of the country (about 2 days).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Department of Transportation, the volume of imported and exported goods transported via rail to, from, or through Chicago is forecast to increase nearly 150 percent between 2010 and 2040.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] CREATE, the Chicago Region Environmental and Transportation Efficiency Program, comprises about 70 programs, including crossovers, overpasses and underpasses, that intend to significantly improve the speed of freight movements in the Chicago area.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Chicago is served by O'Hare International Airport, the world's busiest airport measured by airline operations, on the far Northwest Side, and Midway International Airport on the Southwest Side.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] In 2005, O'Hare was the world's busiest airport by aircraft movements and the second-busiest by total passenger traffic.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] O'Hare is major hub for American Airlines and United Airlines.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Midway is a major operating base for Southwest Airlines.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Both O'Hare and Midway are owned and operated by the City of Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The CTA's Blue Line provides direct rail access to O'Hare, while the Orange Line provides direct rail access to Midway.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Gary/Chicago International Airport and Chicago Rockford International Airport, located in Gary, Indiana and Rockford, Illinois, respectively, can serve as alternative Chicago area airports, however they do not offer as many commercial flights as O'Hare and Midway.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] In recent years the state of Illinois has been leaning towards building an entirely new airport in the Illinois suburbs of Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The City of Chicago is the world headquarters for United Airlines, the world's third-largest airline.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The Port of Chicago consists of several major port facilities within the city of Chicago operated by the Illinois International Port District (formerly known as the Chicago Regional Port District).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The central element of the Port District, Calumet Harbor, is maintained by the U.S.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Electricity for most of northern Illinois is provided by Commonwealth Edison, also known as ComEd.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Their service territory borders Iroquois County to the south, the Wisconsin border to the north, the Iowa border to the west and the Indiana border to the east.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] In northern Illinois, ComEd (a division of Exelon) operates the greatest number of nuclear generating plants in any U.S. state.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Because of this, ComEd reports indicate that Chicago receives about 75% of its electricity from nuclear power.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Recently, the city began installing wind turbines on government buildings to promote renewable energy.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Natural gas is provided by Peoples Gas, a subsidiary of Integrys Energy Group, which is headquartered in Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Domestic and industrial waste was once incinerated but it is now landfilled, mainly in the Calumet area.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] From 1995 to 2008, the city had a blue bag program to divert recyclable refuse from landfills.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Because of low participation in the blue bag programs, the city began a pilot program for blue bin recycling like other cities.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] This proved successful and blue bins were rolled out across the city.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The Illinois Medical District is on the Near West Side.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] It includes Rush University Medical Center, ranked as the second best hospital in the Chicago metropolitan area by *U.S.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] News & World Report* for 2014–16, the University of Illinois Medical Center at Chicago, Jesse Brown VA Hospital, and John H.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Hospital of Cook County, one of the busiest trauma centers in the nation.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] Two of the country's premier academic medical centers, Northwestern Memorial Hospital and the University of Chicago Medical Center, reside in Chicago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The Chicago campus of Northwestern University includes the Feinberg School of Medicine; Northwestern Memorial Hospital, which was ranked as the best hospital in the Chicago metropolitan area by *U.S.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] News & World Report* for 2017–18; the Shirley Ryan AbilityLab (formerly named the Rehabilitation Institute of Chicago), which was ranked the best U.S. rehabilitation hospital by *U.S.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] News & World Report*; the new Prentice Women's Hospital; and Ann & Robert H.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The University of Illinois College of Medicine at UIC is the second-largest medical school in the United States (2,600 students, including those at campuses in Peoria, Rockford and Urbana–Champaign).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] In addition, the Chicago Medical School and Loyola University Chicago's Stritch School of Medicine are located in the suburbs of North Chicago and Maywood, respectively.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/chicago-p03] The Midwestern University Chicago College of Osteopathic Medicine is in Downers Grove.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] Humans first arrived in China during the Paleolithic.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] By the 2nd millennium BCE, dynastic states had emerged.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] The 1st millennium BCE saw political turmoil and cultural growth.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] In 221 BCE, China was unified under the Qin and the succeeding Han dynasty, ushering in two millennia of imperial rule across periods of unity and division.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] Its achievements include the Silk Road and the invention of gunpowder, paper, printing, and the compass.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] After increased Western political, economic, and philosophical influence, the 1911 Revolution overthrew the empire and established the Republic of China (ROC).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] The Warlord Era and Chinese Civil War followed, interrupted by Japan's invasion.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] This ended in a Chinese victory in 1945.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] In 1949, the Chinese Communist Party (CCP) proclaimed the PRC and forced the ROC's retreat to Taiwan.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] CCP attempts to advance communism faltered through famine and political turmoil.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] The reform and opening up that began in 1978 moved China towards a socialist market economy, spurring economic growth.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] The PRC is a unitary state with the CCP as its sole ruling party.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] It is one of the five permanent members of the UN Security Council and a member of many multilateral organizations.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] China is the world's largest manufacturer and makes up about one-fifth of the global economy.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] It is the second largest economy on Earth.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] International organizations have criticized the PRC, alleging authoritarianism and human rights abuses.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] Possessing a large military and nuclear stockpile, China has been described as a superpower due to its influence in geopolitics, science and technology, manufacturing, economics and culture.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] Chinese art and culture has influenced much of Asia.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] Chinese characters are among the oldest writing systems on Earth, with a literary tradition dating back millennia to the Chinese classics.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] China is the birthplace of Confucianism and Daoism, which form the traditional three teachings of Chinese philosophy and folk religion alongside Buddhism.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] Chinese cuisine is diverse and highly regional, with rice as a staple in the south and wheat in the north.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] It has 60 World Heritage Sites, including the Great Wall and Grand Canal.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] The Han, mostly speakers of Sinitic languages, are China's dominant ethnicity, although it is home to 55 recognized minorities, including the Hui, Mongols, Tibetans, Uyghurs, and Zhuang.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] The word "China" has been used in English since the 16th century; however, it was not used by the Chinese themselves during this period.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] Its origin has been traced through Portuguese, Malay, and Persian back to the Sanskrit word *Cīna* (चिन), used in ancient India.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] *Cīna* was first used in early Hindu scripture from the 3rd century BCE to 4th century CE, including the *Mahabharata* and the *Laws of Manu*.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] In 1655, the missionary Martino Martini suggested that the word China is derived ultimately from the name of the Qin dynasty (221–206 BCE) or the prior state of Qin.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] This remains a common etymology, although Indian sources precedes the dynasty, though not the state.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] Another possible source is the ancient Guizhou polity of Yelang, known as *ʐina* in Loloish languages.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] The official name of the modern state is the "People's Republic of China" (中华人民共和国; *Zhōnghuá Rénmín Gònghéguó*).
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] The shorter form of this name is 中国; *Zhōngguó*, from *zhōng* ('central' or 'middle') and *guó* ('state'), a term first used for the demesne of the Western Zhou dynasty.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] The names of ruling imperial dynasties were typically used to refer to the region and state.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] In the 1800s, *Zhongguo* was officially adopted as the name of the country by the Qing dynasty.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] China is sometimes referred to as mainland China or "the Mainland" when distinguishing it from the Republic of China on Taiwan or the PRC's Special Administrative Regions.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] Evidence of early humans such as *Homo erectus* in China dates to the Paleolithic, around 1.7 million years ago, with unconfirmed sites as old as 2 million years ago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] Modern *Homo sapiens* are attested from around 50,000 years ago.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] Following the end of the Last Glacial Period, in about 8,000 BCE, pottery-making Neolithic cultures emerged.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] By the 6000s BCE, sedentary agricultural societies had spread across the lower Yellow River basin.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] These societies became increasingly complex, urbanized, and stratified, but many experienced a population collapse in the late 2000s BCE for unclear reasons.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] After 2000 BCE, a Bronze Age culture emerged in the Central Plain, dubbed the Erlitou culture after its main site.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] Erlitou has been controversially identified with the Xia, the traditionally-accepted first dynasty, but no written records exist to confirm this.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] The Shang dynasty purportedly succeeded the Xia around 1600 BCE, with its early stages tentatively identified with an expansionist state known archaeologically as the Erligang culture.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] The historicity of the Late Shang is attested through divinational writings in the oracle bone script.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] These are the earliest known form of writing in China and the ancestor of modern Chinese characters.
[src:association-for-manufacturing-technology/china-p01] The Shang were overthrown by the Zhou c.
